{"title_page": "Hypoiodous acid", "text_new": "{{Chembox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 477003468\n| ImageFileL1 = Hypoiodige-S\u00e4ure.png\n| ImageFileL2 = Hypoiodous-acid-3D-vdW.png\n| ImageFileR1 = Hypoiodous-acid-3D-balls.png\n| IUPACName = Hypoiodous acid\n| OtherNames = Hypoiodous acid\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 109942\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/HIO/c1-2/h2H\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = GEOVEUCEIQCBKH-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|changed|??}}\n| CASNo = 14332-21-9\n| PubChem = 123340\n| RTECS = \n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 29231\n| SMILES = IO}} \n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = HOI\n| MolarMass = 143.89 g/mol\n| Appearance = \n| Density = \n| Solubility = \n| MeltingPt = \n| BoilingPt = \n| BoilingPt_notes = \n| pKa = 10.5 (in water, estimate)\n| Viscosity = \n| ConjugateBase = [[Hypoiodite]]\n  }}\n|Section7={{Chembox Hazards\n| FlashPt = \n| NFPA-H = \n| NFPA-F = \n| NFPA-R = \n| NFPA-S = \n| RPhrases = \n| SPhrases = \n  }}\n|Section8={{Chembox Related\n| OtherFunction_label = \n| OtherFunction = \n| OtherCompounds = }}\n}}\n\n'''Hypoiodous acid''' is the inorganic compound with the [[chemical formula]] HOI. It forms when an aqueous solution of [[iodine]] is treated with mercuric or silver salts. It rapidly decomposes by [[disproportionation]]:<ref name = \"Wiberg&Holleman\">{{cite book|last1=Holleman|first1=A.F.|title=Inorganic chemistry|date=2001|publisher=Academic Press, W. de Gruyter.|location=San Diego, Calif. : Berlin|isbn=0-12-352651-5|edition=1st English ed., [edited] by Nils Wiberg.}}</ref>\n \n: 5 HOI  \u2192   HIO<sub>3</sub>  +  2I<sub>2</sub>  +  2H<sub>2</sub>O\n \nHypoiodites of alkali and alkaline earth metals can be made in cold dilute solutions if iodine is added to their respective hydroxides.\nHypoiodous acid is a weak acid with a [[Acid dissociation constant|p''K''<sub>a</sub>]] of about 11. The conjugate base is hypoiodite (IO<sup>\u2212</sup>). Salts of this anion can be prepared by treating I<sub>2</sub> with alkali hydroxides. They rapidly disproportionate to form [[iodide]]s and [[iodate]]s.<ref name = \"Wiberg&Holleman\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Hydrogen compounds}}\n{{iodine compounds}}\n\n\n[[Category:Halogen oxoacids]]\n[[Category:Hydrogen compounds]]\n[[Category:Iodine compounds]]\n[[Category:Oxidizing acids]]\n[[Category:Oxidizing agents]]\n\n{{Inorganic-compound-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Chembox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 477003468\n| ImageFileL1 = Hypoiodige-S\u00e4ure.png\n| ImageFileL2 = Hypoiodous-acid-3D-vdW.png\n| ImageFileR1 = Hypoiodous-acid-3D-balls.png\n| IUPACName = Hypoiodous acid\n| OtherNames = Hypoiodous acid\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 109942\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/HIO/c1-2/h2H\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = GEOVEUCEIQCBKH-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|changed|??}}\n| CASNo = 14332-21-9\n| PubChem = 123340\n| RTECS = \n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 29231\n| SMILES = IO}} \n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = HOI\n| MolarMass = 143.89 g/mol\n| Appearance = \n| Density = \n| Solubility = \n| MeltingPt = \n| BoilingPt = \n| BoilingPt_notes = \n| Viscosity = \n| ConjugateBase = [[Hypoiodite]]\n  }}\n|Section7={{Chembox Hazards\n| FlashPt = \n| NFPA-H = \n| NFPA-F = \n| NFPA-R = \n| NFPA-S = \n| RPhrases = \n| SPhrases = \n  }}\n|Section8={{Chembox Related\n| OtherFunction_label = \n| OtherFunction = \n| OtherCompounds = }}\n}}\n\n'''Hypoiodous acid''' is the inorganic compound with the [[chemical formula]] HOI. It forms when an aqueous solution of [[iodine]] is treated with mercuric or silver salts. It rapidly decomposes by [[disproportionation]]:<ref name = \"Wiberg&Holleman\">{{cite book|last1=Holleman|first1=A.F.|title=Inorganic chemistry|date=2001|publisher=Academic Press, W. de Gruyter.|location=San Diego, Calif. : Berlin|isbn=0-12-352651-5|edition=1st English ed., [edited] by Nils Wiberg.}}</ref>\n \n: 5 HOI  \u2192   HIO<sub>3</sub>  +  2I<sub>2</sub>  +  2H<sub>2</sub>O\n \nHypoiodites of alkali and alkaline earth metals can be made in cold dilute solutions if iodine is added to their respective hydroxides.\nHypoiodous acid is a weak acid with a [[Acid dissociation constant|p''K''<sub>a</sub>]] of about 11. The conjugate base is hypoiodite (IO<sup>\u2212</sup>). Salts of this anion can be prepared by treating I<sub>2</sub> with alkali hydroxides. They rapidly disproportionate to form [[iodide]]s and [[iodate]]s.<ref name = \"Wiberg&Holleman\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Hydrogen compounds}}\n{{iodine compounds}}\n\n\n[[Category:Halogen oxoacids]]\n[[Category:Hydrogen compounds]]\n[[Category:Iodine compounds]]\n[[Category:Oxidizing acids]]\n[[Category:Oxidizing agents]]\n\n{{Inorganic-compound-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kaspergm", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added pKa in properties section.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypoiodous_acid"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Singapore}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore\n<!--Difficult to update, so no longer appropriate\n| map2            = COVID-19 Cases in Singapore by Planning Areas.svg\n| legend2         = {{center|Map of planning areas with confirmed (red) coronavirus cases (as of 11 March)}}\n-->\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Singapore]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 23 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=23|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 282<ref name=\"worldometers\">[https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ worldometers.info]</ref><ref name=\"DashBoard\"/><ref name=\"CTSG\"/>\n| deaths          = 6<ref name=\"worldometers\"/><ref name=\"DashBoard\">[https://coronaboard.com COVID-19 Dashboard]</ref><ref name=\"CTSG\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 1,114<ref name=\"worldometers\"/><ref name=\"DashBoard\"/><ref name=\"CTSG\">[https://www.coronatracker.com/country/sg Corona Tracker Overview]</ref>\n| active          = \n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://www.moh.gov.sg/covid-19}}\n| First Case detected: = \n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore''' is part of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The first case of COVID-19 was confirmed on 23 January 2020.<ref name=\"Abdullah 2020\" /> To combat COVID-19, a multi-ministerial committee was formed on 22 January with Minister for National Development [[Lawrence Wong]] and Minister for Health [[Gan Kim Yong]] as the co-chairs and [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]] and [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] and Minister for Finance [[Heng Swee Keat]] as advisors.<ref name=\"ST22Jan\"/><ref>https://www.moh.gov.sg/docs/librariesprovider5/default-document-library/multi-ministry-taskforce-on-wuhan-coronavirus-and-tor---final.pdf</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2020, Singapore announced a stringent set of preventive measures which was collectively called a 'circuit breaker'.\n[[Singapore]] contributed US$500,000 to support [[WHO]] efforts against COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Singapore contributes US$500,000 to support WHO efforts against COVID-19 |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-contributes-s-500-000-to-support-who-covid-19-efforts-12568566 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=CNA |language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Singapore medical cases chart}}\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe top plot shows the total number of cases as a function of time (by date) since 23 January 2020, the date of the first reported case in Singapore. The bottom plot shows the number of new cases as reported each day.\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|colors=orange, blue, red\n| legend=Legend\n| width = 900\n| height = 350\n| xAxisTitle = Date (day/month)\n| yAxisTitle = Total no. of cases (cumulative)\n| y1Title=Confirmed\n| y2Title=Recovered\n| y3Title=Deaths\n| xAxisAngle = -65\n| yGrid= |xGrid= \n| x =  23/1, 24/1, 25/1, 26/1, 27/1, 28/1, 29/1, 30/1, 31/1, 1/2, 2/2, 3/2, 4/2, 5/2, 6/2, 7/2, 8/2, 9/2, 10/2, 11/2, 12/2, 13/2, 14/2, 15/2, 16/2, 17/2, 18/2, 19/2, 20/2, 21/2, 22/2, 23/2, 24/2, 25/2, 26/2, 27/2, 28/2, 29/2, 1/3, 2/3, 3/3, 4/3, 5/3, 6/3, 7/3, 8/3, 9/3, 10/3, 11/3, 12/3, 13/3, 14/3, 15/3, 16/3, 17/3, 18/3, 19/3, 20/3, 21/3, 22/3, 23/3, 24/3, 25/3, 26/3, 27/3, 28/3, 29