{"title_page": "Dara Kass", "text_new": "{{short description|Emergency medicine physician}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Dara Kass\n| workplaces        = [[Columbia University]]<br>[[New York-Presbyterian Hospital]]\n| fields            = [[Emergency Medicine]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Maryland, College Park]], BS, 1998<br>[[SUNY Downstate Medical Center]], MD, 2003\n| known_for         = [[COVID-19]] response\n| children          = 3\n| home_town         = [[Sheepshead Bay]], [[Brooklyn]]\n}}\n\n'''Dara Kass''' is an [[emergency medicine]] physician and Associate Professor of Emergency Medicine at [[Columbia University]] Medical Center. She is also an advocate for advancing the careers of women in medicine. While treating patients during the [[Coronavirus disease|Coronavirus disease (COVID-19)]] pandemic, Kass became infected. Since, she has become a prominent voice advocating for access to personal protective equipment and more effective measures to combat the spread of the disease.\n\n== Education & Early Career ==\nKass was born and raised in [[Brooklyn]], New York. Her mother was an [[emergency medicine]] [[nurse]] at Brookdale Hospital in Brooklyn and inspired Kass's career in medicine.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/capsule-cares/dear-doctor-dara-kass-8c6b419918bb|title=Dear Doctor: Dara Kass|last=Schostak|first=Danielle|date=2019-01-21|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She then attended the [[University of Maryland, College Park]], where she received her [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[neurobiology]] and [[physiology]] in 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buildthewave.org/|title=Build the Wave|website=build-the-wave|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She then returned to Brooklyn to study medicine at [[SUNY Downstate Medical Center|SUNY Downstate Medical School]], where she received her [[Doctor of Medicine]] degree in 2003. From 2003 to 2007, she performed her her residency training in emergency medicine at SUNY Downstate [[Kings County Hospital Center|Kings County Hospital]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Medical Career ==\nKass began her post-residency medical career as an [[attending physician]] at [[Staten Island University Hospital]], where she remained for five years between 2007 and 2013 before moving to [[NYU Langone Medical Center]]. There, she ran the medical school programs in the emergency department, serving as the Director of Undergraduate Medical Education.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2017, she became the Director of Equity and Inclusion and Associate Professor at [[Columbia University Irving Medical Center]] and in July 2018, she became and Assistant Attending Physician at [[New York Presbyterian Medical Center]].\n\n=== COVID-19 Work ===\nWhile treating patients in [[New York City]], Kass became infected with the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|novel coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2)]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/technology/2020/03/coronavirus-covid19-emergency-doctor-new-york-health-illness.html|title=She Was Treating the Infected. Now She Has the Coronavirus.|last=Harris|first=Mary|date=2020-03-26|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> When she first began treating coronavirus patients, she sent her children to live with her parents in New Jersey, while dividing up her home with her husband to prevent infecting her family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/28/822228196/coronavirus-pandemic-takes-a-toll-on-er-doctors-health-and-families|title=Coronavirus Pandemic Takes A Toll On ER Doctors' Health And Families|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> While she was in quarantine recovering from the disease, she continued to advocate for the growing urgency of the situation, noting emergency rooms overwhelmed with patients, shortages of ventilators and personal protective equipment for doctors, and the risks posed to healthcare workers inundated with COVID-19 cases.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glenza|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/27/new-york-coronavirus-elmhurst-hospital|title='It\u2019s what was happening in Italy': the hospital at the center of New York's Covid-19 crisis|date=2020-03-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-01|last2=Rao|first2=Ankita|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Villarreal|first3=Alexandra}}</ref> She has also discussed the risk the pandemic poses to healthcare workers' mental health as they will begin making decisions about whom to treat and whom to not treat in light of hospital supply shortages shortages.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-doctors-nurses-healthcare-supplies-hospitals-2020-3|title='We're going to war and without any ammunition': 6 doctors reveal what it's like to treat coronavirus patients as hospitals scramble for supplies|last=Baylon|first=Claire Molloy, Jacqueline|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> As she began to recover, Kass began virtually consulting with patients using [[telemedicine]] technologies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/nyc-doctor-who-contracted-the-coronavirus-says-the-volume-of-patients-is-just-staggering-2020-04-01|title=NYC doctor who contracted the coronavirus says \u2018the volume of patients is just staggering\u2019|last=Hendrickson|first=V. L.|website=MarketWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nKass has been critical of the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]]'s response to the pandemic, citing inadequate attention paid to the forecasters' projections when they began warning of an emerging crisis in January and a continuing lack of federal oversight and coordination in response to the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/corona-virus-new-york-city-er-doctor|title=\u201cThey Ignored the Warning Signs\u201d: A New York City ER Doctor Explains What She\u2019s Up Against|last=Schama|first=Chloe|website=Vogue|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocacy ===\nKass is an advocate for the advancement of women in medicine. She is a founding member of [[Time's Up (movement)|Time's Up]] Healthcare, working to root out sexual and gender harassment in medicine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90313343/the-timesup-movement-is-coming-to-health-care|title=The #TimesUp movement is coming to healthcare|last=Mohan|first=Pavithra|date=2019-02-28|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Choo|first=Esther K.|last2=van Dis|first2=Jane|last3=Kass|first3=Dara|date=2018-10-25|title=Time\u2019s Up for Medicine? Only Time Will Tell|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/swim/Images/Choo_Times%20Up%20For%20Medicine_NEJM_tcm412-342552.pdf|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=379|issue=17|pages=1592\u20131593|doi=10.1056/NEJMp1809351|issn=0028-4793|pmid=30207825|via=}}</ref> She is also the founder and CEO of [https://feminem.org/ FemInEM], a blog and conference with a mission of promoting gender equity in emergency medicine since its inception in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scopeblog.stanford.edu/2017/07/12/feminem-blog-facilititates-conversations-about-women-in-emergency-medicine/|title=FemInEm blog facilititates conversations about women in emergency medicine|last=Huber|first=Author Jennifer|date=2017-07-12|website=Scope|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kass|first=Dara|last2=Choo|first2=Esther K.|date=2016-10-01|title=When will we have enough women speakers in emergency medicine?|url=https://emj.bmj.com/content/emermed/33/10/680.full.pdf?casa_token=Y-k-5XBUYHAAAAAA:6j6fUkXKMAQqkmM0a7VaMkcM2q9FKmDDdzngE5KMv40j6zlusXvjI-j-Hj66nfvYJgrY9vZXSjVd|journal=Emergency Medicine Journal|language=en|volume=33|issue=10|pages=680\u2013680|doi=10.1136/emermed-2016-206088|issn=1472-0205|pmid=27534976|via=}}</ref> She has also written about the harassment that women in medicine experience even from their patients in the wake of reports that [[Les Moonves]] sexually harassed his physician.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/technology/2018/09/les-moonves-sexual-harassment-doctor-medicine.html|title=Yes, Les Moonves Harassed His Doctor. For Women in Medicine, This Is an Outrage, but Not a Surprise.|last=Dis|first=Dara Kass, Jane van|date=2018-09-12|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She also currently serves as the Director of Equity and Inclusion Initiatives at [[Columbia University Medical Center]].\n\n=== Leadership ===\nIn addition to her work on promoting gender equity in medicine, Kass serves on the board of the nonprofit [[ORGANIZE]], working to reform the organ donation system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://organize.org/board_and_advisors/|title=ORGANIZE|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> She is also a board member of [https://affirmresearch.org/ AFFIRM Research], an organization advocating for a public health approach to solving the epidemic of [[gun violence]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2018/11/10/health-care-professionals-nra-help-us-reduce-gun-deaths-column/1956288002/|title=Medical professionals to NRA: Guns are our lane. Help us reduce deaths or move over.|last=Kass|first=Megan L. Ranney, Heather Sher and Dara|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> She previously served on the Board of Directors for the Academy of Women in Academic Emergency Medicine between 2012\u20132015.\n\n== Awards & Honors ==\n\n*45under45, [[Emergency Medicine Residents' Association]], 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emra.org/be-involved/awards/45under45/|title=EMRA 45 Under 45|website=www.emra.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*Advancement of Women in Academic Emergency Medicine Award, [[Society for Academic Emergency Medicine]], 2019<ref>{{cite press release|last=Roseen|first=Stacey|date=2019-05-15|title=Society for Academic Emergency Medicine Announces 2019 Award Winners|url=https://www.saem.org/docs/default-source/annual-meeting/2019-annual-meeting/saem19-award-winners-press-release.pdf?sfvrsn=669d0dfd_2|location=|publisher=|agency=[[Society for Academic Emergency Medicine]]|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n*Advancing Emergency Care Award, NY [[American College of Emergency Physicians]], 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyacep.org/about-new-york-acep/awards|title=Awards|website=www.nyacep.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nKass is a mother of three children. Her youngest son, Sammy, was diagnosed with a rare condition known as [[alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency]], which results in severely impaired [[liver]] function.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/health/this-doctor-and-mom-donated-part-of-her-liver-to-her-son-in-rare-living-transplant/|title=This Doctor and Mom Donated Part of Her Liver to Her Son in Rare Living Transplant|website=PEOPLE.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> While some infants outgrow the condition, her son did not. As a result, she  chose to act as a [[Liver transplantation|living donor]], donating a part of her liver to her son and recounted the experience in ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/05/13/donating-an-organ-to-my-son/|title=Donating an Organ to My Son|last=Kass|first=Dara|last2=M.D|date=2016-05-13|website=Well|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> She has since advocated for revamping federal rules around U.S.'s organ donation system to increase access to organ donations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/08/americas-deadly-failure-on-organ-donations/|title=America\u2019s deadly failure on organ donations|last=Kass|first=Dara|date=2020-01-09|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n<references />{{Authority control|ORCID=0000-0003-3075-9547}}\n[[Category:1970s births]]\n[[Category:Women in medicine]]\n[[Category:Emergency physicians]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:SUNY Downstate Medical Center alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Emergency medicine physician}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Dara Kass\n| workplaces        = [[Columbia University]]<br>[[New York-Presbyterian Hospital]]\n| fields            = [[Emergency Medicine]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Maryland, College Park]], BS, 1998<br>[[SUNY Downstate Medical Center]], MD, 2003\n| known_for         = [[COVID-19]] response\n| children          = 3\n| home_town         = [[Sheepshead Bay]], [[Brooklyn]]\n}}\n\n'''Dara Kass''' is an [[emergency medicine]] physician and Associate Professor of Emergency Medicine at [[Columbia University]] Medical Center. She is also an advocate for advancing the careers of women in medicine. While treating patients during the [[Coronavirus disease|Coronavirus disease (COVID-19)]] pandemic, Kass became infected. Since, she has become a prominent voice advocating for access to personal protective equipment and more effective measures to combat the spread of the disease.\n\n== Education & Early Career ==\nKass was born and raised in [[Brooklyn]], New York. Her mother was an [[emergency medicine]] [[nurse]] at Brookdale Hospital in Brooklyn and inspired Kass's career in medicine.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/capsule-cares/dear-doctor-dara-kass-8c6b419918bb|title=Dear Doctor: Dara Kass|last=Schostak|first=Danielle|date=2019-01-21|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She then attended the [[University of Maryland, College Park]], where she received her [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[neurobiology]] and [[physiology]] in 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buildthewave.org/|title=Build the Wave|website=build-the-wave|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She then returned to Brooklyn to study medicine at [[SUNY Downstate Medical Center|SUNY Downstate Medical School]], where she received her [[Doctor of Medicine]] degree in 2003. From 2003 to 2007, she performed her her residency training in emergency medicine at SUNY Downstate [[Kings County Hospital Center|Kings County Hospital]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Medical Career ==\nKass began her post-residency medical career as an [[attending physician]] at [[Staten Island University Hospital]], where she remained for five years between 2007 and 2013 before moving to [[NYU Langone Medical Center]]. There, she ran the medical school programs in the emergency department, serving as the Director of Undergraduate Medical Education.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2017, she became the Director of Equity and Inclusion and Associate Professor at [[Columbia University Irving Medical Center]] and in July 2018, she became and Assistant Attending Physician at [[New York Presbyterian Medical Center]].\n\n=== COVID-19 Work ===\nWhile treating patients in [[New York City]], Kass became infected with the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|novel coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2)]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/technology/2020/03/coronavirus-covid19-emergency-doctor-new-york-health-illness.html|title=She Was Treating the Infected. Now She Has the Coronavirus.|last=Harris|first=Mary|date=2020-03-26|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> When she first began treating coronavirus patients, she sent her children to live with her parents in New Jersey, while dividing up her home with her husband to prevent infecting her family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/28/822228196/coronavirus-pandemic-takes-a-toll-on-er-doctors-health-and-families|title=Coronavirus Pandemic Takes A Toll On ER Doctors' Health And Families|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> While she was in quarantine recovering from the disease, she continued to advocate for the growing urgency of the situation, noting emergency rooms overwhelmed with patients, shortages of ventilators and personal protective equipment for doctors, and the risks posed to healthcare workers inundated with COVID-19 cases.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glenza|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/27/new-york-coronavirus-elmhurst-hospital|title='It\u2019s what was happening in Italy': the hospital at the center of New York's Covid-19 crisis|date=2020-03-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-01|last2=Rao|first2=Ankita|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Villarreal|first3=Alexandra}}</ref> She has also discussed the risk the pandemic poses to healthcare workers' mental health as they will begin making decisions about whom to treat and whom to not treat in light of hospital supply shortages shortages.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-doctors-nurses-healthcare-supplies-hospitals-2020-3|title='We're going to war and without any ammunition': 6 doctors reveal what it's like to treat coronavirus patients as hospitals scramble for supplies|last=Baylon|first=Claire Molloy, Jacqueline|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> As she began to recover, Kass began virtually consulting with patients using [[telemedicine]] technologies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/nyc-doctor-who-contracted-the-coronavirus-says-the-volume-of-patients-is-just-staggering-2020-04-01|title=NYC doctor who contracted the coronavirus says \u2018the volume of patients is just staggering\u2019|last=Hendrickson|first=V. L.|website=MarketWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nKass has been critical of the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]]'s response to the pandemic, citing inadequate attention paid to the forecasters' projections when they began warning of an emerging crisis in January and a continuing lack of federal oversight and coordination in response to the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/corona-virus-new-york-city-er-doctor|title=\u201cThey Ignored the Warning Signs\u201d: A New York City ER Doctor Explains What She\u2019s Up Against|last=Schama|first=Chloe|website=Vogue|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocacy ===\nKass is an advocate for the advancement of women in medicine. She is a founding member of [[Time's Up (movement)|Time's Up]] Healthcare, working to root out sexual and gender harassment in medicine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90313343/the-timesup-movement-is-coming-to-health-care|title=The #TimesUp movement is coming to healthcare|last=Mohan|first=Pavithra|date=2019-02-28|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Choo|first=Esther K.|last2=van Dis|first2=Jane|last3=Kass|first3=Dara|date=2018-10-25|title=Time\u2019s Up for Medicine? Only Time Will Tell|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/swim/Images/Choo_Times%20Up%20For%20Medicine_NEJM_tcm412-342552.pdf|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=379|issue=17|pages=1592\u20131593|doi=10.1056/NEJMp1809351|issn=0028-4793|pmid=30207825|via=}}</ref> She is also the founder and CEO of [https://feminem.org/ FemInEM], a blog and conference with a mission of promoting gender equity in emergency medicine since its inception in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scopeblog.stanford.edu/2017/07/12/feminem-blog-facilititates-conversations-about-women-in-emergency-medicine/|title=FemInEm blog facilititates conversations about women in emergency medicine|last=Huber|first=Author Jennifer|date=2017-07-12|website=Scope|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kass|first=Dara|last2=Choo|first2=Esther K.|date=2016-10-01|title=When will we have enough women speakers in emergency medicine?|url=https://emj.bmj.com/content/emermed/33/10/680.full.pdf?casa_token=Y-k-5XBUYHAAAAAA:6j6fUkXKMAQqkmM0a7VaMkcM2q9FKmDDdzngE5KMv40j6zlusXvjI-j-Hj66nfvYJgrY9vZXSjVd|journal=Emergency Medicine Journal|language=en|volume=33|issue=10|pages=680\u2013680|doi=10.1136/emermed-2016-206088|issn=1472-0205|pmid=27534976|via=}}</ref> She has also written about the harassment that women in medicine experience even from their patients in the wake of reports that [[Les Moonves]] sexually harassed his physician.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/technology/2018/09/les-moonves-sexual-harassment-doctor-medicine.html|title=Yes, Les Moonves Harassed His Doctor. For Women in Medicine, This Is an Outrage, but Not a Surprise.|last=Dis|first=Dara Kass, Jane van|date=2018-09-12|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She also currently serves as the Director of Equity and Inclusion Initiatives at [[Columbia University Medical Center]].\n\n=== Leadership ===\nIn addition to her work on promoting gender equity in medicine, Kass serves on the board of the nonprofit [[ORGANIZE]], working to reform the organ donation system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://organize.org/board_and_advisors/|title=ORGANIZE|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> She is also a board member of [https://affirmresearch.org/ AFFIRM Research], an organization advocating for a public health approach to solving the epidemic of [[gun violence]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2018/11/10/health-care-professionals-nra-help-us-reduce-gun-deaths-column/1956288002/|title=Medical professionals to NRA: Guns are our lane. Help us reduce deaths or move over.|last=Kass|first=Megan L. Ranney, Heather Sher and Dara|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> She previously served on the Board of Directors for the Academy of Women in Academic Emergency Medicine between 2012-2015.\n\n== Awards & Honors ==\n\n*45under45, [[Emergency Medicine Residents' Association]], 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emra.org/be-involved/awards/45under45/|title=EMRA 45 Under 45|website=www.emra.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*Advancement of Women in Academic Emergency Medicine Award, [[Society for Academic Emergency Medicine]], 2019<ref>{{cite press release|last=Roseen|first=Stacey|date=2019-05-15|title=Society for Academic Emergency Medicine Announces 2019 Award Winners|url=https://www.saem.org/docs/default-source/annual-meeting/2019-annual-meeting/saem19-award-winners-press-release.pdf?sfvrsn=669d0dfd_2|location=|publisher=|agency=[[Society for Academic Emergency Medicine]]|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n*Advancing Emergency Care Award, NY [[American College of Emergency Physicians]], 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyacep.org/about-new-york-acep/awards|title=Awards|website=www.nyacep.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nKass is a mother of three children. Her youngest son, Sammy, was diagnosed with a rare condition known as [[alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency]], which results in severely impaired [[liver]] function.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/health/this-doctor-and-mom-donated-part-of-her-liver-to-her-son-in-rare-living-transplant/|title=This Doctor and Mom Donated Part of Her Liver to Her Son in Rare Living Transplant|website=PEOPLE.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> While some infants outgrow the condition, her son did not. As a result, she  chose to act as a [[Liver transplantation|living donor]], donating a part of her liver to her son and recounted the experience in ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/05/13/donating-an-organ-to-my-son/|title=Donating an Organ to My Son|last=Kass|first=Dara|last2=M.D|date=2016-05-13|website=Well|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> She has since advocated for revamping federal rules around U.S.'s organ donation system to increase access to organ donations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/08/americas-deadly-failure-on-organ-donations/|title=America\u2019s deadly failure on organ donations|last=Kass|first=Dara|date=2020-01-09|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n<references />{{Authority control|ORCID=0000-0003-3075-9547}}\n[[Category:1970s births]]\n[[Category:Women in medicine]]\n[[Category:Emergency physicians]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:SUNY Downstate Medical Center alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLeadership:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2012-2015 \u2192 2012\u20132015", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dara_Kass"}
{"title_page": "Anthony van Dyck", "text_new": "{{Redirect2|Van Dyck|Vandyck|other persons with the surname|Van Dyck (surname)}}\n{{for|the racehorse|Anthony Van Dyck (horse)}}\n{{short description|17th-century Flemish Baroque artist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Anthony van Dyck\n| image         = Anthonyvandyckselfportrait.jpeg\n| caption       = ''[[Self-portrait with a sunflower|Self-Portrait with a Sunflower]]'' (after 1633)\n| birth_name    = Antoon van Dyck\n| birth_date    = 22 March 1599\n| birth_place   = [[Antwerp]], [[Spanish Netherlands#Spanish Netherlands|Spanish Netherlands]] (modern-day [[Belgium]])\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1641|12|9|1599|3|22|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = London\n| nationality   = [[Spanish Netherlands|Flemish]]\n| field         = Painting\n| training      = [[Hendrick van Balen]],<br /> [[Peter Paul Rubens]]\n| movement      = [[Baroque]]\n}}\n'''Sir Anthony van Dyck''' ({{IPA-nl|v\u0251n \u02c8d\u025bi\u032fk}}, many variant spellings;<ref>[http://www.getty.edu/vow/ULANFullDisplay?find=Anthony+van+Dyck&role=&nation=&prev_page=1&subjectid=500115190 ULAN entry]. Originally \"van Dijck\", with the [[IJ (digraph)|\"IJ\" digraph]], in Dutch. Anthony is the English for the Dutch Anthonis or Antoon, though Anthonie, Antonio or Anthonio was also used; in French he is often Antoine, in Italian Anthonio or Antonio. In English a capitalised \"Van\" in Van Dyck was more usual until recent decades (used by Waterhouse for example), and \"Dyke\" was often used during his lifetime and later (and is usual for the beard style).</ref> 22 March 1599&nbsp;\u2013 9 December 1641) was a [[Flemish Baroque painting|Flemish Baroque artist]] who became the leading [[court painter]] in England after success in the [[Southern Netherlands]] and Italy.\n\nThe seventh child of Frans van Dyck, a wealthy [[Antwerp (city)|Antwerp]] silk merchant, Anthony painted from an early age. He was successful as an independent painter his late teens, and became a master in the [[Guild of Saint Luke|Antwerp guild]] in 1618. By this time he was working in the studio of the leading northern painter of the day, [[Peter Paul Rubens]], who became a major influence on his work.  Van Dyck worked in London for some months in 1621, then returned to Flanders for a brief time, before travelling to Italy, where he stayed until 1627, mostly in Genoa. In the late 1620s he completed his greatly admired ''Iconography'' series of portrait [[etching]]s, mostly of other artists.  He spent five years in Flanders after his return from Italy, and from 1630 was court painter for the archduchess [[Isabella Clara Eugenia|Isabella]], Habsburg Governor of Flanders. In 1632 he returned to London to be the main court painter, at the request of [[Charles I of England]].\n\nWith the exception of [[Hans Holbein the Younger|Holbein]], van Dyck and his contemporary [[Diego Vel\u00e1zquez]] were the first painters of pre-eminent talent to work mainly as court portraitists, revolutionising the genre. He is best known for his portraits of the aristocracy, most notably Charles I, and his family and associates. Van Dyck became the dominant influence on [[English school of painting|English portrait-painting]] for the next 150 years. He also painted [[mythological]] and [[biblical]] subjects, including altarpieces, displayed outstanding facility as a draughtsman, and was an important innovator in [[watercolour]] and [[etching]].  His superb brushwork, apparently rather quickly painted, can usually be distinguished from the large areas painted by his many assistants.  His portrait style changed considerably between the different countries he worked in, culminating in the relaxed elegance of his last English period.  His influence extends into the modern period. The [[Van Dyke beard]] is named after him. During his lifetime, Charles I granted him a [[Knight Bachelor|knighthood]], and he was buried in [[St Paul's Cathedral]], an indication of his standing at the time of his death.\n\n==Life and work==\n[[File:Anthonis van Dyck 008b.jpg|thumb|left|''Self-portrait'', 1613\u201314]]\n\n===Education===\nAntoon van Dyck (his Flemish name) was born to prosperous parents in Antwerp. His father was Frans van Dyck, a silk merchant, and his mother was Maria, daughter of Dirk Cupers and Catharina Conincx.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Van_Dyck,_Anthony_(DNB00) |title=Van Dyck Anthony |first=Lionel Henry |last=Cust |publisher= |volume=Volume 58 |accessdate=28 April 2018 |via=Wikisource}}</ref> He was baptised on 23 March 1599 (as Anthonio).<ref>Antwerp, S.A.A., Parochieregisters, Doopakten, 30/03/1592 - 26/06/1606, fol. 147, 23-03-1599 Anthonio Van Dijck, retrieved by the Jordaens Van Dyck Panel Paintings Project (www.jordaensvandyck.org) on 06/04/2017.</ref> His talent was evident very early, and he was studying painting with [[Hendrick van Balen]] by 1609, and became an independent painter around 1615, setting up a workshop with his even younger friend [[Jan Brueghel the Younger]].<ref>Brown, p. 15.</ref> By the age of fifteen he was already a highly accomplished artist, as his ''Self-portrait'', 1613\u201314, shows.<ref>Vlieghe, Hans. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=AS_NXFoY0M4C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Flemish Art and Architecture, 1585\u20131700]'', Yale University Press, 2004, p. 124. {{ISBN|0-300-10469-3}}</ref> He was admitted to the Antwerp painters' [[Guild of Saint Luke]] as a free master by February 1618.<ref>Martin, Gregory. ''The Flemish School, 1600-1900'', National Gallery Catalogues, p. 26, 1970, National Gallery, London, {{ISBN|0-901791-02-4}}</ref> Within a few years he was to be the chief assistant to the dominant master of Antwerp, and the whole of Northern Europe, [[Peter Paul Rubens]], who made much use of sub-contracted artists as well as his own large workshop. His influence on the young artist was immense. Rubens referred to the nineteen-year-old van Dyck as \"the best of my pupils\".<ref>Brown, p. 17.</ref>\n\nThe origins and exact nature of their relationship are unclear. It has been speculated that van Dyck was a pupil of Rubens from about 1613, as even his early work shows little trace of van Balen's style, but there is no clear evidence for this.<ref name=\"EW\">Ellis Waterhouse, ''Painting in Britain, 1530-1790'', 4th Edn, 1978, pp. 70-77, Penguin Books (now Yale History of Art series)</ref> At the same time the dominance of Rubens in the relatively small and declining city of Antwerp probably explains why, despite his periodic returns to the city, van Dyck spent most of his career abroad.<ref name=\"EW\" /> In 1620, in Rubens's contract for the major commission for the ceiling of the [[Carolus Borromeuskerk]], the [[Jesuit]] church at Antwerp (lost to fire in 1718), van Dyck is specified as one of the \"discipelen\" who was to execute the paintings to Rubens' designs.<ref name=\"Martin, op and page cit\">Martin, op and page cit.</ref> Unlike van Dyck, Rubens worked for most of the courts of Europe, but avoided exclusive attachment to any of them.\n\n===Italy===\n[[File:Anthonis van Dyck 012.jpg|thumb|Genoan hauteur from the Lomellini family, 1623]]\nIn 1620, at the instigation of [[George Villiers, 1st Duke of Buckingham|George Villiers, Marquess of Buckingham]], van Dyck went to England for the first time where he worked for King [[James I of England]], receiving \u00a3100.<ref name=\"EW\" /> It was in [[London]] in the collection of the [[Thomas Howard, 21st Earl of Arundel|Earl of Arundel]] that he first saw the work of [[Titian]], whose use of colour and subtle modeling of form would prove transformational, offering a new stylistic language that would enrich the compositional lessons learned from Rubens.<ref>Brown, page 19.</ref>\n\nAfter about four months, he returned to Flanders, but left in late 1621 for Italy, where he remained for six years. There he studied the Italian masters while starting his career as a successful portraitist. He was already presenting himself as a figure of consequence, annoying the rather bohemian Northern artist's colony in [[Rome]], says [[Giovan Pietro Bellori]], by appearing with \"the pomp of [[Zeuxis]] ... his behaviour was that of a nobleman rather than an ordinary person, and he shone in rich garments. Since he was accustomed in the circle of Rubens to noblemen, and being naturally of elevated mind, and anxious to make himself distinguished, he therefore wore\u2014as well as silks\u2014a hat with feathers and brooches, gold chains across his chest, and was accompanied by servants.\"<ref>[[Michael Levey|Levey, Michael]], ''Painting at Court'', Weidenfeld & Nicolson, London, 1971, pp. 124-5</ref>\n[[File:Anthony Van Dyck, by Peter Paul Rubens.jpg|thumb|225px|left|''Anthony van Dyck'', by [[Peter Paul Rubens]] (1627\u201328)]]\nHe was mostly based in [[Genoa]], although he also travelled extensively to other cities, and stayed for some time in [[Palermo]] in [[Sicily]], where he was quarantined during the 1624 plague, one of the worst in Sicily's history. There he produced an important series of paintings of the city's plague saint [[Saint Rosalia]]. His depictions of a young woman with flowing blonde hair wearing a Franciscan cowl and reaching down toward the city of Palermo in its peril, became the standard iconography of the saint from that time onward and was extremely influential for Italian Baroque painters, from [[Luca Giordano]] to [[Pietro Novelli]]. Versions include those in [[Saint Rosalia (Anthony van Dyck)|Madrid]], [[Saint Rosalia Crowned by Angels (Houston)|Houston]], [[Saint Rosalia Crowned by Angels (London)|London]], [[Saint Rosalie Interceding for the Plague\u2013Stricken of Palermo|New York]] and [[Saint Rosalia Crowned by Angels (Palermo)|Palermo]], as well as [[Saint Rosalia Interceding for the City of Palermo]] in Puerto Rico, and [[Coronation of Saint Rosalia]] in Vienna. Van Dyck's series of St Rosalia paintings have been studied by [[Gauvin Alexander Bailey]] and [[Xavier F. Salomon]], both of whom curated or co-curated exhibitions devoted to the theme of Italian art and the plague.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/29/arts/design/desperately-painting-the-plague.html</ref><ref>https://go.gale.com/ps/anonymous?id=GALE%7CA284449813&sid=googleScholar&v=2.1&it=r&linkaccess=abs&issn=00036536&p=AONE&sw=w</ref><ref>https://www.dulwichpicturegallery.org.uk/about/exhibitions-archive/exhibitions-archive-by-date/2012-van-dyck-in-sicily/</ref> Recently the New York Times published an article about the Metropolitan Museum of Art's painting of Saint Rosalia by Van Dyck in the context of the [[Covid-19]] virus.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/arts/design/van-dyck-metropolitan-museum-virus.html</ref>.\n\nFor the Genoese aristocracy, then in a final flush of prosperity, he developed a full-length portrait style, drawing on [[Paolo Veronese|Veronese]] and Titian as well as Rubens' style from his own period in Genoa, where extremely tall but graceful figures look down on the viewer with great hauteur. In 1627, he went back to Antwerp where he remained for five years, painting more affable portraits which still made his Flemish patrons look as stylish as possible. A life-size group portrait of twenty-four City Councillors of [[Brussels]] he painted for the council-chamber was destroyed in 1695.{{sfn|Cust|1899}} He was evidently very charming to his patrons, and, like Rubens, well able to mix in aristocratic and court circles, which added to his ability to obtain commissions. By 1630, he was described as the court painter of the Habsburg Governor of Flanders, the Archduchess Isabella. In this period he also produced many religious works, including large [[altarpiece]]s, and began his printmaking.\n\n===London===\n[[File:Sir-Anthony-van-Dyck-Lord-John-Stuart-and-His-Brother-Lord-Bernard-Stuart.jpg|thumb|''[[Lord John Stuart and his Brother, Lord Bernard Stuart]]'', c. 1638, exemplifies the more intimate, but still elegant style he developed in England]]\nKing Charles I was the most passionate collector of art among the [[House of Stuart|Stuart kings]], and saw painting as a way of promoting his elevated view of the monarchy. In 1628, he bought the fabulous collection that the [[Charles I, Duke of Mantua|Duke of Mantua]] was forced to sell, and he had been trying since his accession in 1625 to bring leading foreign painters to England. In 1626, he was able to persuade [[Orazio Gentileschi]] to settle in England, later to be joined by his daughter [[Artemisia Gentileschi|Artemisia]] and some of his sons. Rubens was an especial target, who eventually in 1630 came on a diplomatic mission, which included painting, and he later sent Charles more paintings from Antwerp. Rubens was very well-treated during his nine-month visit, during which he was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]]. Charles's court portraitist, [[Daniel Mytens]], was a somewhat pedestrian Dutchman. Charles was very short, less than {{convert|5|ft|m}} tall, and presented challenges to a portrait artist.\n\nVan Dyck had remained in touch with the English court and helped King Charles's agents in their search for pictures. He sent some of his own works, including a self portrait (1623) with [[Endymion Porter]], one of Charles's agents ''Rinaldo and [[Armida]]'' (1629), and a religious picture for the Queen. He had also painted Charles's sister, [[Elizabeth of Bohemia|Queen Elizabeth of Bohemia]], at [[The Hague]] in 1632. In April of that year, van Dyck returned to London and was taken under the wing of the court immediately, being knighted in July and at the same time receiving a pension of \u00a3200 a year, in the grant of which he was described as ''[[Principal Painter in Ordinary|principalle Paynter in ordinary to their majesties]]''.<ref name=\"Grosvenor Gallery Stephens 1887 p. 14\">{{cite book |author=Grosvenor Gallery |last2=Stephens |first2=F.G. |title=Exhibition of the Works of Sir Anthony Van Dyck |publisher=H. Good and Son, Printers |year=1887 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v5gTAAAAQAAJ |access-date=1 May 2019 |page=14 |quote=About the end of March or the beginning of April, 1632, Van Dyck arrived in England ; he was almost immediately appointed Principal Painter in Ordinary to the King, knighted, presented with a gold chain, similar to that which had been given to ...}}</ref><ref name=\"Sharpe Lake 1993 p. 223\">{{cite book |last=Sharpe |first=K. |last2=Lake |first2=P. |title=Culture and Politics in Early Stuart England |publisher=Stanford University Press |year=1993 |isbn=978-0-8047-2261-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0AjPfEmjXXsC&pg=PA223 |access-date=1 May 2019 |page=223}}</ref> He was well paid for his paintings in addition to this, at least in theory, as King Charles did not actually pay over his pension for five years, and reduced the price of many paintings. He was provided with a house on the [[River Thames]] at [[Blackfriars, London|Blackfriars]], then just outside the [[City of London|City]], thus avoiding the monopoly of the [[Worshipful Company of Painter-Stainers]]. A suite of rooms in [[Eltham Palace]], no longer used by the royal family, was also put at his disposal as a country retreat. His Blackfriars studio was frequently visited by the King and Queen (later a special causeway was built to ease their access), who hardly sat for another painter while van Dyck lived.<ref name=\"EW\" />{{sfn|Cust|1899}}\n\n[[File:Anthonis van Dyck 044.jpg|thumb|left|''[[Charles I at the Hunt]]'', c. 1635, Louvre]]\nHe was an immediate success in England, rapidly painting a large number of portraits of the King and [[Henrietta Maria of France|Queen Henrietta Maria]], as well as their children. Many portraits were done in several versions, to be sent as diplomatic gifts or given to supporters of the increasingly embattled king. Altogether van Dyck has been estimated to have painted forty portraits of King Charles himself, as well as about thirty of the Queen, nine of the [[Thomas Wentworth, 1st Earl of Strafford|Earl of Strafford]], and multiple ones of other courtiers.<ref>Gaunt, William, ''English Court Painting''</ref> He painted many of the court, and also himself and his mistress, Margaret Lemon.\n\nIn England he developed a version of his style which combined a relaxed elegance and ease with an understated authority in his subjects which was to dominate English portrait-painting to the end of the 18th century. Many of these portraits have a lush landscape background. His portraits of Charles on horseback updated the grandeur of Titian's Emperor Charles V, but even more effective and original is his portrait of Charles dismounted in the [[Louvre]]: \"Charles is given a totally natural look of instinctive sovereignty, in a deliberately informal setting where he strolls so negligently that he seems at first glance nature's gentleman rather than England's King\".<ref>Levey p. 128</ref> Although his portraits have created the classic idea of \"[[Cavalier]]\" style and dress, in fact a majority of his most important patrons in the nobility, such as [[Philip Wharton, 4th Baron Wharton|Lord Wharton]] and the Earls of [[Francis Russell, 4th Earl of Bedford|Bedford]], [[Algernon Percy, 10th Earl of Northumberland|Northumberland]] and [[Philip Herbert, 4th Earl of Pembroke|Pembroke]], took the [[Roundhead|Parliamentarian]] side in the [[English Civil War]] that broke out soon after his death.{{sfn|Cust|1899}}\n[[File:Anton Van Dyck - Christ carrying the Cross - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|''Christ carrying the Cross'']]\nThe King [[Queen in Council|in]] [[Privy Council of England|Council]] by [[letters patent]] granted van Dyck ''[[denization|denizenship]]'' in 1638, and he married Mary, the daughter of [[John Ruthven, 3rd Earl of Gowrie#Family|Patrick Ruthven]], who, although the title was forfeited, styled himself [[Earl of Gowrie#Lords Ruthven (1488)|Lord Ruthven]].<ref>Cokayne, G. E., et al, ''The Complete Peerage'', vol.iv, London, 1916, p. 385n</ref> She was a [[Lady-in-waiting]] to the Queen, in 1639\u201340; this may have been instigated by the King in an attempt to keep him in England.<ref name=\"EW\" /> He had spent most of 1634 in Antwerp, returning the following year, and in 1640\u201341, as the Civil War loomed, spent several months in Flanders and [[France]]. In 1640 he accompanied prince [[John II Casimir of Poland|John Casimir]] of [[Poland]] after he was freed from French imprisonment.<ref name=\"treasures\">{{cite web |url=http://swiadectwotestimony.republika.pl/dyck_vasas.html |title=Portret kr\u00f3lewicza |work=Treasures... |accessdate=29 August 2008 |language=pl |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627044344/http://swiadectwotestimony.republika.pl/dyck_vasas.html |archivedate=27 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\nA letter dated 13 August 1641, from Lady Roxburghe in England to a correspondent in The Hague, reported that van Dyck was recuperating from a long illness.<ref name=\"Jaffe\">Michael Jaff\u00e9. \"Dyck, Anthony van\". ''Grove Art Online. Oxford Art Online''. Oxford University Press. Web.</ref> In November, van Dyck's condition worsened, and he returned to England from Paris, where he had gone to paint [[Cardinal Richelieu]].<ref name=\"Jaffe\" /> He died in London on 9 December 1641.\n\n==Portraits and other works==\n[[File:Anton van Dyck - Samson and Delilah - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|left|''Samson and Delilah'', c. 1630, a history painting in the manner of Rubens. The use of saturated colours reveals van Dyck's study of [[Titian]]]]\n[[File:Anthonis van Dyck 013.jpg|thumb|''[[Henrietta Maria]] and the [[dwarfism|dwarf]], [[Sir Jeffrey Hudson]]'', 1633]]\n\nIn the 17th century, demand for portraits was stronger than for other types of work. Van Dyck tried to persuade Charles to commission large-scale series on the history of the [[Order of the Garter]] for the [[Banqueting House, Whitehall]], for which Rubens had earlier done the huge ceiling paintings (sending them from Antwerp). A sketch for one wall remains, but by 1638 Charles was too short of money to proceed.<ref name=\"EW\" /> This was a problem Vel\u00e1zquez did not have, but equally van Dyck's daily life was not encumbered by trivial court duties as Vel\u00e1zquez's was. In his visits to Paris in his last years van Dyck tried to obtain the commission to paint the Grande Gallerie of the [[Louvre]] without success.<ref>Levey, op cit p. 136</ref>\n\nA list of history paintings produced by van Dyck in England survives. It was compiled by van Dyck's biographer Bellori, based on information from [[Sir Kenelm Digby]].  None of these works appear to remain, except the ''Eros and Psyche'' done for the King (below).<ref name=\"EW\" /> But many other works, rather more religious than mythological, do survive, and though they are very fine, they do not reach the heights of Vel\u00e1zquez's history paintings. Earlier ones remain very much within the style of Rubens, although some of his Sicilian works are individualistic.\n\nVan Dyck's portraits flattered more than Vel\u00e1zquez's. When [[Sophia of Hanover|Sophia, later Electoress of Hanover]], first met Queen Henrietta Maria, in exile in Holland in 1641, she wrote: \"Van Dyck's handsome portraits had given me so fine an idea of the beauty of all English ladies, that I was surprised to find that the Queen, who looked so fine in painting, was a small woman raised up on her chair, with long skinny arms and teeth like defence works projecting from her mouth...\"<ref name=\"EW\" />\n[[File:The Cheeke Sisters by Van Dyck.jpg|thumb|left|''The Cheeke Sisters'', a late double portrait]]\nSome critics have blamed van Dyck for diverting a nascent, tougher English portrait tradition\u2014of painters such as [[William Dobson]], [[Robert Walker (painter)|Robert Walker]] and [[Isaac Fuller]]\u2014into what certainly became elegant blandness in the hands of many of van Dyck's successors, like [[Peter Lely|Lely]] or [[Godfrey Kneller|Kneller]].<ref name=\"EW\" /> The conventional view has always been more favourable: \"When Van Dyck came hither he brought Face-Painting to us; ever since which time ... England has excel'd all the World in that great Branch of the Art\" (Jonathan Richardson: ''An Essay on the Theory of Painting'', 1715, 41). Thomas Gainsborough is reported to have said on his deathbed \"We are all going to heaven, and Van Dyck is of the Company.\"{{sfn|Cust|1899}}\n\nA fairly small number of [[Landscape art|landscape]] pen and wash drawings or [[watercolour]]s made in England played an important part in introducing the Flemish watercolour landscape tradition to England. Some are studies, which reappear in the background of paintings, but many are signed and dated and were probably regarded as finished works to be given as presents. Several of the most detailed are of [[Rye, East Sussex|Rye]], a port for ships to the Continent, suggesting that van Dyck did them casually whilst waiting for wind or tide to improve.<ref>Royalton-Kisch, Martin. ''The Light of Nature, Landscape Drawings and Watercolours by Van Dyck and his Contemporaries'', British Museum Press, 1999, {{ISBN|0-7141-2621-7}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Printmaking==\nProbably during his period in Antwerp after his return from Italy, van Dyck began his ''Iconography'', eventually a very large series of [[old master print|prints]] with half-length portraits of eminent contemporaries. Van Dyck produced drawings, and for eighteen of the portraits he himself [[etching|etched]] with great brilliance the heads and the main outlines of the figure, for an [[engraving|engraver]] to work up: \"Portrait etching had scarcely had an existence before his time, and in his work it suddenly appears at the highest point ever reached in the art\".<ref name=\"Hind\">Arthur M. Hind, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=bxFb8nN_wUQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false A History of Engraving and Etching]'', p. 165, Houghton Mifflin Co. 1923 (in USA), reprinted Dover Publications, 1963 {{ISBN|0-486-20954-7}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Van Dyck Pieter Brueghel the Younger.jpg|thumb|[[Pieter Brueghel the Younger]] from the ''Iconography''; etching by van Dyck]]\nHowever, for most of the series he left the whole [[printmaking]] work to specialists, who mostly engraved everything after his drawings. His own etched plates appear not to have been published commercially until after his death, and early states are very rare.<ref name=\"Decker\">Becker, D. P., in KL Spangeberg (ed), ''Six Centuries of Master Prints'', Cincinnati Art Museum, 1993, no. 72, {{ISBN|0-931537-15-0}}</ref> Most of his plates were printed after only his work had been done. Some exist in further [[state (printmaking)|states]] after engraving had been added, sometimes obscuring his etching. He continued to add to the series until at least his departure for England, and presumably added [[Inigo Jones]] whilst in London.\n\nThe series was a great success, but was his only venture into printmaking; portraiture probably paid better, and he was constantly in demand. At his death there were eighty plates by others, of which fifty-two were of artists, as well as his own eighteen. The plates were bought by a publisher; with the plates reworked periodically as they wore out they continued to be printed for centuries, and the series added to, so that it reached over two hundred portraits by the late 18th century. In 1851, the plates were bought by the ''Calcographie du [[Louvre]]''.<ref name=\"Decker\" />\n\nThe ''Iconography'' was highly influential as a commercial model for reproductive printmaking; now forgotten series of portrait prints were enormously popular until the advent of [[photography]]: \"the importance of this series was enormous, and it provided a repertory of images that were plundered by portrait painters throughout Europe over the next couple of centuries\".{{sfn|Cust|1899}} Van Dyck's brilliant etching style, which depended on open lines and dots, was in marked contrast to that of the other great portraitist in prints of the period, [[Rembrandt]], and had little influence until the 19th century, when it had a great influence on artists such as [[James McNeill Whistler|Whistler]] in the last major phase of portrait etching.<ref name=\"Hind\" /> [[Hyatt Mayor]] wrote:\n\n{{Quote|Etchers have studied Van Dyck ever since, for they can hope to approximate his brilliant directness, whereas nobody can hope to approach the complexity of Rembrandt's portraits.<ref>Mayor, Alpheus Hyatt. ''Prints and People'', Metropolitan Museum of Art. Princeton, 1971, no. 433-35, {{ISBN|0-691-00326-2}}</ref>}}\n\n==Studio==\nVan Dyck's success led him to maintain a large workshop in London, which became \"virtually a production line for portraits\". According to a visitor he usually only made a drawing on paper, which was then enlarged onto canvas by an assistant; he then painted the head himself. The costume in which the client wished to be painted was left at the studio and often with the unfinished canvas sent out to artists specialised in rendering such clothing.{{sfn|Cust|1899}} In his last years these studio collaborations accounted for some decline in the quality of work.<ref>Brown, pp. 84-6.</ref>\n\nIn addition many copies untouched by him, or virtually so, were produced by the workshop, as well as by professional copyists and later painters. The number of paintings ascribed to him had by the 19th century become huge, as with [[Rembrandt]], [[Titian]] and others. However, most of his assistants and copyists could not approach the refinement of his manner, so compared to many masters consensus among [[art historian]]s on attributions to him is usually relatively easy to reach, and museum labelling is now mostly updated ([[English country houses|country house]] attributions may be more dubious in some cases).\n\nThe relatively few names of his assistants that are known are Dutch or Flemish. He probably preferred to use trained Flemings, as no equivalent English training existed in this period.<ref name=\"EW\" /> Van Dyck's enormous influence on English art does not come from a tradition handed down through his pupils; in fact it is not possible to document a connection to his studio for any English painter of any significance.<ref name=\"EW\" /> Dutchman [[Adriaen Hanneman]] (1604\u20131671) returned to his native [[Den Haag|The Hague]] in 1638 to become the leading portraitist there.<ref>Rudi Ekkart and Quentin Buvelot (eds), ''Dutch Portraits, The Age of Rembrandt and Frans Hals'', Mauritshuis/National Gallery/Waanders Publishers, Zwolle, p. 138 QB, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-85709-362-9}}</ref> Flemish painter [[Pieter Thijs]] studied in van Dyck's workshop as one of van Dyck's last pupils.  He became a very successful portrait and history painter in his native Antwerp.<ref name=ox>Hans Vlieghe, \"Thijs, Pieter.\" Grove Art Online. Oxford Art Online. Oxford University Press. Web. 22 August 2019</ref>\n\n[[File:Sir Anthony Van Dyck - Charles I (1600-49) - Google Art Project.jpg|270px|thumb|''[[Charles I in Three Positions]]'' (1635-36), a triple portrait of Charles I, was sent to Rome for [[Bernini]] to model a bust on]]\n\n==Legacy==\nMuch later, the styles worn by his models provided the names of the [[Van Dyke beard]] for the sharply pointed and trimmed goatees popular for men in his day, and the [[Clothing terminology#Costume historian's terms|van Dyke collar]], \"a wide collar across the shoulders edged copiously with lace\".<ref name=\"beard\">{{Cite book |title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Clothing through World History |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-313-33664-5 |editor-last=Condra |editor-first=Jill |edition=1 |volume=2 |publication-place=United States |pages=103 |language=English |asin=B01FJ09WHC |quote=His style coined the names of the van Dyke beard, for the sharply pointed and trimmed goatees popular for men in the first half of the century, and the van Dyke collar, a wide collar across the shoulders edged copiously with lace. |<!--access-date=September 11, 2018-->}}</ref> During the reign of [[George III of England|George III]], a generic \"Cavalier\" fancy-dress costume called a ''Van Dyke'' was popular; Gainsborough's ''[[The Blue Boy]]'' is wearing such a ''Van Dyke'' outfit.  In 1774 [[Derby porcelain]] advertised a figure, after a portrait by [[Johann Zoffany]], of \"[[George III of England|the King]] in a Vandyck dress\".<ref>[[:File:George III, Queen Charlotte and their Six Eldest Children.png|The painting, Royal Collection]]; Honey, W.B., ''Old English Porcelain'', p, 147, 1977 (3rd edn.), Faber and Faber, {{ISBN|0571049028}}</ref>\n\nA confusing number of different pigments used in painting have been called \"Vandyke brown\" (mostly in English-language sources).  Some predate van Dyck, and it is not clear that he used any of them.<ref>\"Vandyke brown\", ''Pigment Compendium'', by Nicholas Eastaugh, Valentine Walsh, Tracey Chaplin, Ruth Siddall, p. 388, 2008, Routledge, {{ISBN|1136373926}}, 9781136373923, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=P7vbXHR2mTYC&pg=PA388 google books]</ref> [[Van Dyke brown (printing)|Van Dyke brown]] is an early photographic printing process using the same colour.\n\nWhen van Dyck was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1632, he [[anglicized]] his name to Vandyke.<ref name=\"Massie\">{{Cite book |title=The Royal Stuarts: A History of the Family That Shaped Britain |last=Massie |first=Allan |publisher=St. Martin's Griffin |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-250-02492-3 |publication-date=5 February 2013 |pages=191 |language=English |type=paperback |quote=Van Dyck was knighted and anglicised his name to Vandyke.}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nThe British [[Royal Collection]], which still contains many of his paintings, has a total of twenty-six paintings.<ref>[http://www.royalcollection.org.uk/collection-search/van%20Dyck?f&#91;0&#93;=sort_creator%3Asir%20anthony%20van%20dyck%20%281599-1641%29%20%28artist%29 Royal Collection] Paintings by Van Dyck</ref> The [[National Gallery, London]] (fourteen works), The [[Museo del Prado|Museo del Prado (Spain)]] (twenty-five Works, such as Self-portrait with Endymion Porter, The Metal Serpent, Christ Crowned with Thorns, The Pretention, Portrait of Mary Ruthven, the painter's Wife), The [[Louvre]] in [[Paris]] (eighteen works), The [[Alte Pinakothek]] in [[Munich]], the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] and the [[Frick Collection]] have examples of his portrait style. [[Wilton House]] still holds the works he did for one of his main patrons, the Earl of Pembroke, including his largest work, a huge family group portrait with ten main figures. Spanish museums own a rich presence of this artist in addition to The Prado's ensemble; The [[Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum]] preserves ''the Portrait of Jacques Le Roy'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museothyssen.org/en/collection/artists/dyck-anthony-van/portrait-jacques-roy|title=Portrait of Jacques Le Roy|website=Museo Nacional Thyssen-Bornemisza|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> property of The Carmen Thyssen-Bornemisza Collection but also on display at the Museum there's  a ''Crucified Christ'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museothyssen.org/en/collection/artists/dyck-anthony-van/christ-cross|title=Christ on the Cross|website=Museo Nacional Thyssen-Bornemisza|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> and The [[Bilbao Fine Arts Museum]] houses a great ''Lamentation before the dead Christ''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museobilbao.com/in/obras-comentadas/van-dyck-anton-57|title=Annotated works {{!}} The Bilbao Fine Arts Museum|website=www.museobilbao.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> In 2008, [[Patrimonio Nacional|Patrimonio Nacional of Spain]] recovered a ''Martyrdom of Saint Sebastian'' and returned it to [[El Escorial|The Escorial Monastery]], two centuries after its removal and, subsequently, The [[Real Academia de Bellas Artes de San Fernando]] has revealed as its own a long-stored painting, added to another, ''The Virgin with the Child with the repentant sinners'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.academiacolecciones.com/pinturas/inventario.php?id=0323|title=Dyck, Antonio van - La Virgen y el Ni\u00f1o con los pecadores arrepentidos|last=Fernando|first=Real Academia de BBAA de San|website=Academia Colecciones|language=es|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> in addition the institution has an original sketch. In addition, in December 2017, a ''Virgin with Child'', which is kept in The [[Museum Cerralbo]] and was previously considered the work of [[Mateo Cerezo]], was revealed as the painter's original after an exhaustive study and restoration project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturaydeporte.gob.es/mcerralbo/coleccion/coleccion0/pintura/anton-van-dyck.html|title=Anton Van Dyck|website=www.culturaydeporte.gob.es|language=es|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Finally, The [[Museu de Belles Arts de Val\u00e8ncia|Museum of Fine Arts of Valencia]] owns an ''Equestrian Portrait of Don Francisco de Moncada'' (currently undergoing restoration, April 2020).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museobellasartesvalencia.gva.es/es/noticias/-/asset_publisher/OCD94WMhKnYX/content/-retrato-ecuestre-de-francisco-de-moncada-de-van-dyck|title='Retrato ecuestre de Francisco de Moncada' de Van Dyck - Noticias - Generalitat Valenciana|website=www.museobellasartesvalencia.gva.es|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Tate Britain]] held the exhibition ''Van Dyck & Britain'' in 2009.<ref>Karen Hearn (ed.), ''[http://www.tate.org.uk/britain/exhibitions/vandyck/ Van Dyck & Britain]'', [[Tate Publishing Ltd|Tate Publishing]], 2009. {{ISBN|978-1-85437-795-1}}.</ref> In 2016 the [[Frick Collection]] in New York had an exhibition \"Van Dyck: The Anatomy of Portraiture\", the first major survey of the artist's work in the United States in over two decades.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.frick.org/exhibitions/van_dyck |title=Past Exhibition: Van Dyck |publisher=The Frick Collection}}</ref>\n\n[[Basilica of St. Joseph Proto-Cathedral|The Basilica of St. Joseph Proto-Cathedral]] in Bardstown Kentucky houses three van Dycks.\n\nThe estate of the [[Charles Spencer, 9th Earl Spencer|Earl Spencer]] at [[Althorp]] houses a small collection of van Dycks including ''War and Peace'' (Portrait of Sir [[George Digby, 2nd Earl of Bristol]], English Royalist politician with [[William Russell, 1st Duke of Bedford]]), which is the most valuable painting in the collection and the favourite of the earl.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4718214/As-a-child-I-loved-the-glamour-of-these-men.html |title=As a child I loved the glamour of these men |date=1999-08-20 |access-date=2019-04-04 |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"220\" heights=\"220\">\nFile:Anthonis van Dyck 004.jpg|''[[Christ Crowned with Thorns (van Dyck)|Christ Crowned with Thorns]]'' (c. 1620) in the [[Prado]]\nFile:Anthonis van Dyck 016.jpg|''Elena Grimaldi'', Genoa, 1623\nFile:Anton van Dyck - Nicolas Lanier - Google Art Project.jpg|''[[Nicholas Lanier]]'', 1628\nFile:Anton van Dyck - The Vision of the Blessed Hermann Joseph - Google Art Project.jpg|''[[The Vision of the Blessed Hermann Joseph]]'' c. 1629\u201330\nFile:Anthonis van Dyck 048.jpg|''[[Rest on the Flight into Egypt (van Dyck)|Rest on the Flight into Egypt]]'', ca. 1630, [[Alte Pinakothek]], [[Munich]]\nFile:Anthonis van Dyck 021.jpg|''Marie-Louise de Tassis'', Antwerp, 1630\nFile:Anthony van Dyck - Charles I (1600-49) with M. de St Antoine - Google Art Project.jpg|''[[Charles I with M. de St Antoine]]'', 1633\nFile:Van dyck tomaso 1634 1635.jpg|''[[Equestrian Portrait of Thomas Francis, Prince of Carignano]]'', 1634\nFile:Anthony Van Dyck - Katherine, Countess of Chesterfield, and Lucy, Countess of Huntingdon - Google Art Project.jpg|''Katherine, Countess of Chesterfield, and Lucy, Countess of Huntingdon'', c. 1636\u201340, oil on canvas, [[Yale Center for British Art]]\nFile:Anthonis van Dyck - Equestrian Portrait of Charles I - National Gallery, London.jpg|''[[Equestrian Portrait of Charles I]]'', c. 1637\u201338\nFile:Anthonis van Dyck 001.jpg|''[[Cupid and Psyche (van Dyck)|Cupid and Psyche]]'', 1638\nFile:Anthony Van Dyck - Portrait of Mary Hill, Lady Killigrew - Google Art Project.jpg|''[[Portrait of Mary Hill, Lady Killigrew]]'', 1638\nFile:Bewening van Christus, Anthony van Dyck, (1635), Koninklijk Museum voor Schone Kunsten Antwerpen, 404.jpg|''Bewening van Christus'', 1635, [[Royal Museum of Fine Arts Antwerp]]\nFile:Anthony van Dyck - De apostel Mattheus - L'apotre Matthieu - Fonds Generet - Koning Boudewijnstichting - Fondation Roi Baudouin.jpg|The apostle Matthew, [[Royal Museum of Fine Arts Antwerp]]\nFile:War and Peace Van Dyck.jpg|Portrait of Sir [[George Digby, 2nd Earl of Bristol]], English Royalist politician with [[William Russell, 1st Duke of Bedford]] (\"War and Peace\"), 1637, [[Althorp]]\nFile:Anthony van Dyck - Portrait of Jacques Le Roy - WGA07397.jpg|''Portrait of Jacques Le Roy'', Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum, Madrid.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of paintings by Anthony van Dyck]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Brown, Christopher: ''Van Dyck 1599-1641''. Royal Academy Publications, 1999. {{ISBN|0-900946-66-0}}\n*{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Van Dyck, Sir Anthony|volume=27}}\n*{{cite DNB |wstitle=Van Dyck, Anthony |volume=58 |first=Lionel Henry |last=Cust}}\n*{{cite CE1913|wstitle=Antoon Van Dyck|volume=5|first=George Charles|last=Williamson}}\n*{{cite ODNB |first=Jeremy |last=Wood |title=Dyck, Sir Anthony Van (1599\u20131641) |id=28081}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.paul-mellon-centre.ac.uk/collections/archive-collections/oliver-millar The Oliver Millar Archive]; research papers of [[Oliver Millar]], British art historian and a leading authority on Anthony van Dyck\n* [http://www.nga.gov/content/ngaweb/features/slideshows/sir-anthony-van-dyck.html?view=grid#slide_1 Van Dyck at the National Gallery of Art]\n* {{Art UK bio}}\n* [http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/artists/anthony-van-dyck The National Gallery: Van Dyck, with short biography]\n* [http://www.npg.org.uk/whatson/van-dyck/home.php The National Portrait Gallery: Van Dyck]\n* {{Royal Collection|404429|Sir Anthony Van Dyck|[[Peter Paul Rubens]]}}\n*[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/65202/rec/17 ''Vermeer and The Delft School''], a full text exhibition catalog from The Metropolitan Museum of Art, which has material on Anthony van Dyck\n*[http://jordaensvandyck.org/ Jordaens Van Dyck Panel Paintings Project]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-court}}\n{{s-bef|before=\u2014|}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Principal Painter in Ordinary]] to the King| years=\u20131641}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Peter Lely|Sir Peter Lely]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Van Dyck}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dyck, Anthony Van}}\n[[Category:1599 births]]\n[[Category:1641 deaths]]\n[[Category:Flemish etchers]]\n[[Category:Flemish portrait painters]]\n[[Category:Flemish history painters]]\n[[Category:Flemish Baroque painters]]\n[[Category:History of Antwerp]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:English portrait painters]]\n[[Category:Principal Painters in Ordinary]]\n[[Category:Baroque printmakers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Antwerp Guild of Saint Luke]]\n[[Category:Artists from Antwerp]]\n[[Category:Stepney family]]\n[[Category:Burials at St Paul's Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Pupils of Peter Paul Rubens]]\n[[Category:Belgian Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect2|Van Dyck|Vandyck|other persons with the surname|Van Dyck (surname)}}\n{{for|the racehorse|Anthony Van Dyck (horse)}}\n{{short description|17th-century Flemish Baroque artist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Anthony van Dyck\n| image         = Anthonyvandyckselfportrait.jpeg\n| caption       = ''[[Self-portrait with a sunflower|Self-Portrait with a Sunflower]]'' (after 1633)\n| birth_name    = Antoon van Dyck\n| birth_date    = 22 March 1599\n| birth_place   = [[Antwerp]], [[Spanish Netherlands#Spanish Netherlands|Spanish Netherlands]] (modern-day [[Belgium]])\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1641|12|9|1599|3|22|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = London\n| nationality   = [[Spanish Netherlands|Flemish]]\n| field         = Painting\n| training      = [[Hendrick van Balen]],<br /> [[Peter Paul Rubens]]\n| movement      = [[Baroque]]\n}}\n'''Sir Anthony van Dyck''' ({{IPA-nl|v\u0251n \u02c8d\u025bi\u032fk}}, many variant spellings;<ref>[http://www.getty.edu/vow/ULANFullDisplay?find=Anthony+van+Dyck&role=&nation=&prev_page=1&subjectid=500115190 ULAN entry]. Originally \"van Dijck\", with the [[IJ (digraph)|\"IJ\" digraph]], in Dutch. Anthony is the English for the Dutch Anthonis or Antoon, though Anthonie, Antonio or Anthonio was also used; in French he is often Antoine, in Italian Anthonio or Antonio. In English a capitalised \"Van\" in Van Dyck was more usual until recent decades (used by Waterhouse for example), and \"Dyke\" was often used during his lifetime and later (and is usual for the beard style).</ref> 22 March 1599&nbsp;\u2013 9 December 1641) was a [[Flemish Baroque painting|Flemish Baroque artist]] who became the leading [[court painter]] in England after success in the [[Southern Netherlands]] and Italy.\n\nThe seventh child of Frans van Dyck, a wealthy [[Antwerp (city)|Antwerp]] silk merchant, Anthony painted from an early age. He was successful as an independent painter his late teens, and became a master in the [[Guild of Saint Luke|Antwerp guild]] in 1618. By this time he was working in the studio of the leading northern painter of the day, [[Peter Paul Rubens]], who became a major influence on his work.  Van Dyck worked in London for some months in 1621, then returned to Flanders for a brief time, before travelling to Italy, where he stayed until 1627, mostly in Genoa. In the late 1620s he completed his greatly admired ''Iconography'' series of portrait [[etching]]s, mostly of other artists.  He spent five years in Flanders after his return from Italy, and from 1630 was court painter for the archduchess [[Isabella Clara Eugenia|Isabella]], Habsburg Governor of Flanders. In 1632 he returned to London to be the main court painter, at the request of [[Charles I of England]].\n\nWith the exception of [[Hans Holbein the Younger|Holbein]], van Dyck and his contemporary [[Diego Vel\u00e1zquez]] were the first painters of pre-eminent talent to work mainly as court portraitists, revolutionising the genre. He is best known for his portraits of the aristocracy, most notably Charles I, and his family and associates. Van Dyck became the dominant influence on [[English school of painting|English portrait-painting]] for the next 150 years. He also painted [[mythological]] and [[biblical]] subjects, including altarpieces, displayed outstanding facility as a draughtsman, and was an important innovator in [[watercolour]] and [[etching]].  His superb brushwork, apparently rather quickly painted, can usually be distinguished from the large areas painted by his many assistants.  His portrait style changed considerably between the different countries he worked in, culminating in the relaxed elegance of his last English period.  His influence extends into the modern period. The [[Van Dyke beard]] is named after him. During his lifetime, Charles I granted him a [[Knight Bachelor|knighthood]], and he was buried in [[St Paul's Cathedral]], an indication of his standing at the time of his death.\n\n==Life and work==\n[[File:Anthonis van Dyck 008b.jpg|thumb|left|''Self-portrait'', 1613\u201314]]\n\n===Education===\nAntoon van Dyck (his Flemish name) was born to prosperous parents in Antwerp. His father was Frans van Dyck, a silk merchant, and his mother was Maria, daughter of Dirk Cupers and Catharina Conincx.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Van_Dyck,_Anthony_(DNB00) |title=Van Dyck Anthony |first=Lionel Henry |last=Cust |publisher= |volume=Volume 58 |accessdate=28 April 2018 |via=Wikisource}}</ref> He was baptised on 23 March 1599 (as Anthonio).<ref>Antwerp, S.A.A., Parochieregisters, Doopakten, 30/03/1592 - 26/06/1606, fol. 147, 23-03-1599 Anthonio Van Dijck, retrieved by the Jordaens Van Dyck Panel Paintings Project (www.jordaensvandyck.org) on 06/04/2017.</ref> His talent was evident very early, and he was studying painting with [[Hendrick van Balen]] by 1609, and became an independent painter around 1615, setting up a workshop with his even younger friend [[Jan Brueghel the Younger]].<ref>Brown, p. 15.</ref> By the age of fifteen he was already a highly accomplished artist, as his ''Self-portrait'', 1613\u201314, shows.<ref>Vlieghe, Hans. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=AS_NXFoY0M4C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Flemish Art and Architecture, 1585\u20131700]'', Yale University Press, 2004, p. 124. {{ISBN|0-300-10469-3}}</ref> He was admitted to the Antwerp painters' [[Guild of Saint Luke]] as a free master by February 1618.<ref>Martin, Gregory. ''The Flemish School, 1600-1900'', National Gallery Catalogues, p. 26, 1970, National Gallery, London, {{ISBN|0-901791-02-4}}</ref> Within a few years he was to be the chief assistant to the dominant master of Antwerp, and the whole of Northern Europe, [[Peter Paul Rubens]], who made much use of sub-contracted artists as well as his own large workshop. His influence on the young artist was immense. Rubens referred to the nineteen-year-old van Dyck as \"the best of my pupils\".<ref>Brown, p. 17.</ref>\n\nThe origins and exact nature of their relationship are unclear. It has been speculated that van Dyck was a pupil of Rubens from about 1613, as even his early work shows little trace of van Balen's style, but there is no clear evidence for this.<ref name=\"EW\">Ellis Waterhouse, ''Painting in Britain, 1530-1790'', 4th Edn, 1978, pp. 70-77, Penguin Books (now Yale History of Art series)</ref> At the same time the dominance of Rubens in the relatively small and declining city of Antwerp probably explains why, despite his periodic returns to the city, van Dyck spent most of his career abroad.<ref name=\"EW\" /> In 1620, in Rubens's contract for the major commission for the ceiling of the [[Carolus Borromeuskerk]], the [[Jesuit]] church at Antwerp (lost to fire in 1718), van Dyck is specified as one of the \"discipelen\" who was to execute the paintings to Rubens' designs.<ref name=\"Martin, op and page cit\">Martin, op and page cit.</ref> Unlike van Dyck, Rubens worked for most of the courts of Europe, but avoided exclusive attachment to any of them.\n\n===Italy===\n[[File:Anthonis van Dyck 012.jpg|thumb|Genoan hauteur from the Lomellini family, 1623]]\nIn 1620, at the instigation of [[George Villiers, 1st Duke of Buckingham|George Villiers, Marquess of Buckingham]], van Dyck went to England for the first time where he worked for King [[James I of England]], receiving \u00a3100.<ref name=\"EW\" /> It was in [[London]] in the collection of the [[Thomas Howard, 21st Earl of Arundel|Earl of Arundel]] that he first saw the work of [[Titian]], whose use of colour and subtle modeling of form would prove transformational, offering a new stylistic language that would enrich the compositional lessons learned from Rubens.<ref>Brown, page 19.</ref>\n\nAfter about four months, he returned to Flanders, but left in late 1621 for Italy, where he remained for six years. There he studied the Italian masters while starting his career as a successful portraitist. He was already presenting himself as a figure of consequence, annoying the rather bohemian Northern artist's colony in [[Rome]], says [[Giovan Pietro Bellori]], by appearing with \"the pomp of [[Zeuxis]] ... his behaviour was that of a nobleman rather than an ordinary person, and he shone in rich garments. Since he was accustomed in the circle of Rubens to noblemen, and being naturally of elevated mind, and anxious to make himself distinguished, he therefore wore\u2014as well as silks\u2014a hat with feathers and brooches, gold chains across his chest, and was accompanied by servants.\"<ref>[[Michael Levey|Levey, Michael]], ''Painting at Court'', Weidenfeld & Nicolson, London, 1971, pp. 124-5</ref>\n[[File:Anthony Van Dyck, by Peter Paul Rubens.jpg|thumb|225px|left|''Anthony van Dyck'', by [[Peter Paul Rubens]] (1627\u201328)]]\nHe was mostly based in [[Genoa]], although he also travelled extensively to other cities, and stayed for some time in [[Palermo]] in [[Sicily]], where he was quarantined during the 1624 plague, one of the worst in Sicily's history. There he produced an important series of paintings of the city's plague saint [[Saint Rosalia]]. His depictions of a young woman with flowing blonde hair wearing a Franciscan cowl and reaching down toward the city of Palermo in its peril, became the standard iconography of the saint from that time onward and was extremely influential for Italian Baroque painters, from [[Luca Giordano]] to [[Pietro Novelli]]. Versions include those in [[Saint Rosalia (Anthony van Dyck)|Madrid]], [[Saint Rosalia Crowned by Angels (Houston)|Houston]], [[Saint Rosalia Crowned by Angels (London)|London]], [[Saint Rosalie Interceding for the Plague\u2013Stricken of Palermo|New York]] and [[Saint Rosalia Crowned by Angels (Palermo)|Palermo]], as well as [[Saint Rosalia Interceding for the City of Palermo]] in Puerto Rico, and [[Coronation of Saint Rosalia]] in Vienna. Van Dyck's series of St Rosalia paintings have been studied by [[Gauvin Alexander Bailey]] and [[Xavier F. Salomon]], both of whom curated or co-curated exhibitions devoted to the theme of Italian art and the plague.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/29/arts/design/desperately-painting-the-plague.html</ref><ref>https://go.gale.com/ps/anonymous?id=GALE%7CA284449813&sid=googleScholar&v=2.1&it=r&linkaccess=abs&issn=00036536&p=AONE&sw=w</ref><ref>https://www.dulwichpicturegallery.org.uk/about/exhibitions-archive/exhibitions-archive-by-date/2012-van-dyck-in-sicily/</ref> Recently the New York Times published an article about the Metropolitan Museum of Art's painting of Saint Rosalia by Van Dyck in the context of the [[Covid-19]] virus.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/arts/design/van-dyck-metropolitan-museum-virus.html</ref>.\n\nFor the Genoese aristocracy, then in a final flush of prosperity, he developed a full-length portrait style, drawing on [[Paolo Veronese|Veronese]] and Titian as well as Rubens' style from his own period in Genoa, where extremely tall but graceful figures look down on the viewer with great hauteur. In 1627, he went back to Antwerp where he remained for five years, painting more affable portraits which still made his Flemish patrons look as stylish as possible. A life-size group portrait of twenty-four City Councillors of [[Brussels]] he painted for the council-chamber was destroyed in 1695.{{sfn|Cust|1899}} He was evidently very charming to his patrons, and, like Rubens, well able to mix in aristocratic and court circles, which added to his ability to obtain commissions. By 1630, he was described as the court painter of the Habsburg Governor of Flanders, the Archduchess Isabella. In this period he also produced many religious works, including large [[altarpiece]]s, and began his printmaking.\n\n===London===\n[[File:Sir-Anthony-van-Dyck-Lord-John-Stuart-and-His-Brother-Lord-Bernard-Stuart.jpg|thumb|''[[Lord John Stuart and his Brother, Lord Bernard Stuart]]'', c. 1638, exemplifies the more intimate, but still elegant style he developed in England]]\nKing Charles I was the most passionate collector of art among the [[House of Stuart|Stuart kings]], and saw painting as a way of promoting his elevated view of the monarchy. In 1628, he bought the fabulous collection that the [[Charles I, Duke of Mantua|Duke of Mantua]] was forced to sell, and he had been trying since his accession in 1625 to bring leading foreign painters to England. In 1626, he was able to persuade [[Orazio Gentileschi]] to settle in England, later to be joined by his daughter [[Artemisia Gentileschi|Artemisia]] and some of his sons. Rubens was an especial target, who eventually in 1630 came on a diplomatic mission, which included painting, and he later sent Charles more paintings from Antwerp. Rubens was very well-treated during his nine-month visit, during which he was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]]. Charles's court portraitist, [[Daniel Mytens]], was a somewhat pedestrian Dutchman. Charles was very short, less than {{convert|5|ft|m}} tall, and presented challenges to a portrait artist.\n\nVan Dyck had remained in touch with the English court and helped King Charles's agents in their search for pictures. He sent some of his own works, including a self portrait (1623) with [[Endymion Porter]], one of Charles's agents ''Rinaldo and [[Armida]]'' (1629), and a religious picture for the Queen. He had also painted Charles's sister, [[Elizabeth of Bohemia|Queen Elizabeth of Bohemia]], at [[The Hague]] in 1632. In April of that year, van Dyck returned to London and was taken under the wing of the court immediately, being knighted in July and at the same time receiving a pension of \u00a3200 a year, in the grant of which he was described as ''[[Principal Painter in Ordinary|principalle Paynter in ordinary to their majesties]]''.<ref name=\"Grosvenor Gallery Stephens 1887 p. 14\">{{cite book |author=Grosvenor Gallery |last2=Stephens |first2=F.G. |title=Exhibition of the Works of Sir Anthony Van Dyck |publisher=H. Good and Son, Printers |year=1887 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v5gTAAAAQAAJ |access-date=1 May 2019 |page=14 |quote=About the end of March or the beginning of April, 1632, Van Dyck arrived in England ; he was almost immediately appointed Principal Painter in Ordinary to the King, knighted, presented with a gold chain, similar to that which had been given to ...}}</ref><ref name=\"Sharpe Lake 1993 p. 223\">{{cite book |last=Sharpe |first=K. |last2=Lake |first2=P. |title=Culture and Politics in Early Stuart England |publisher=Stanford University Press |year=1993 |isbn=978-0-8047-2261-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0AjPfEmjXXsC&pg=PA223 |access-date=1 May 2019 |page=223}}</ref> He was well paid for his paintings in addition to this, at least in theory, as King Charles did not actually pay over his pension for five years, and reduced the price of many paintings. He was provided with a house on the [[River Thames]] at [[Blackfriars, London|Blackfriars]], then just outside the [[City of London|City]], thus avoiding the monopoly of the [[Worshipful Company of Painter-Stainers]]. A suite of rooms in [[Eltham Palace]], no longer used by the royal family, was also put at his disposal as a country retreat. His Blackfriars studio was frequently visited by the King and Queen (later a special causeway was built to ease their access), who hardly sat for another painter while van Dyck lived.<ref name=\"EW\" />{{sfn|Cust|1899}}\n\n[[File:Anthonis van Dyck 044.jpg|thumb|left|''[[Charles I at the Hunt]]'', c. 1635, Louvre]]\nHe was an immediate success in England, rapidly painting a large number of portraits of the King and [[Henrietta Maria of France|Queen Henrietta Maria]], as well as their children. Many portraits were done in several versions, to be sent as diplomatic gifts or given to supporters of the increasingly embattled king. Altogether van Dyck has been estimated to have painted forty portraits of King Charles himself, as well as about thirty of the Queen, nine of the [[Thomas Wentworth, 1st Earl of Strafford|Earl of Strafford]], and multiple ones of other courtiers.<ref>Gaunt, William, ''English Court Painting''</ref> He painted many of the court, and also himself and his mistress, Margaret Lemon.\n\nIn England he developed a version of his style which combined a relaxed elegance and ease with an understated authority in his subjects which was to dominate English portrait-painting to the end of the 18th century. Many of these portraits have a lush landscape background. His portraits of Charles on horseback updated the grandeur of Titian's Emperor Charles V, but even more effective and original is his portrait of Charles dismounted in the [[Louvre]]: \"Charles is given a totally natural look of instinctive sovereignty, in a deliberately informal setting where he strolls so negligently that he seems at first glance nature's gentleman rather than England's King\".<ref>Levey p. 128</ref> Although his portraits have created the classic idea of \"[[Cavalier]]\" style and dress, in fact a majority of his most important patrons in the nobility, such as [[Philip Wharton, 4th Baron Wharton|Lord Wharton]] and the Earls of [[Francis Russell, 4th Earl of Bedford|Bedford]], [[Algernon Percy, 10th Earl of Northumberland|Northumberland]] and [[Philip Herbert, 4th Earl of Pembroke|Pembroke]], took the [[Roundhead|Parliamentarian]] side in the [[English Civil War]] that broke out soon after his death.{{sfn|Cust|1899}}\n[[File:Anton Van Dyck - Christ carrying the Cross - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|''Christ carrying the Cross'']]\nThe King [[Queen in Council|in]] [[Privy Council of England|Council]] by [[letters patent]] granted van Dyck ''[[denization|denizenship]]'' in 1638, and he married Mary, the daughter of [[John Ruthven, 3rd Earl of Gowrie#Family|Patrick Ruthven]], who, although the title was forfeited, styled himself [[Earl of Gowrie#Lords Ruthven (1488)|Lord Ruthven]].<ref>Cokayne, G. E., et al, ''The Complete Peerage'', vol.iv, London, 1916, p. 385n</ref> She was a [[Lady-in-waiting]] to the Queen, in 1639\u201340; this may have been instigated by the King in an attempt to keep him in England.<ref name=\"EW\" /> He had spent most of 1634 in Antwerp, returning the following year, and in 1640\u201341, as the Civil War loomed, spent several months in Flanders and [[France]]. In 1640 he accompanied prince [[John II Casimir of Poland|John Casimir]] of [[Poland]] after he was freed from French imprisonment.<ref name=\"treasures\">{{cite web |url=http://swiadectwotestimony.republika.pl/dyck_vasas.html |title=Portret kr\u00f3lewicza |work=Treasures... |accessdate=29 August 2008 |language=pl |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627044344/http://swiadectwotestimony.republika.pl/dyck_vasas.html |archivedate=27 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\nA letter dated 13 August 1641, from Lady Roxburghe in England to a correspondent in The Hague, reported that van Dyck was recuperating from a long illness.<ref name=\"Jaffe\">Michael Jaff\u00e9. \"Dyck, Anthony van\". ''Grove Art Online. Oxford Art Online''. Oxford University Press. Web.</ref> In November, van Dyck's condition worsened, and he returned to England from Paris, where he had gone to paint [[Cardinal Richelieu]].<ref name=\"Jaffe\" /> He died in London on 9 December 1641.\n\n==Portraits and other works==\n[[File:Anton van Dyck - Samson and Delilah - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|left|''Samson and Delilah'', c. 1630, a history painting in the manner of Rubens. The use of saturated colours reveals van Dyck's study of [[Titian]]]]\n[[File:Anthonis van Dyck 013.jpg|thumb|''[[Henrietta Maria]] and the [[dwarfism|dwarf]], [[Sir Jeffrey Hudson]]'', 1633]]\n\nIn the 17th century, demand for portraits was stronger than for other types of work. Van Dyck tried to persuade Charles to commission large-scale series on the history of the [[Order of the Garter]] for the [[Banqueting House, Whitehall]], for which Rubens had earlier done the huge ceiling paintings (sending them from Antwerp). A sketch for one wall remains, but by 1638 Charles was too short of money to proceed.<ref name=\"EW\" /> This was a problem Vel\u00e1zquez did not have, but equally van Dyck's daily life was not encumbered by trivial court duties as Vel\u00e1zquez's was. In his visits to Paris in his last years van Dyck tried to obtain the commission to paint the Grande Gallerie of the [[Louvre]] without success.<ref>Levey, op cit p. 136</ref>\n\nA list of history paintings produced by van Dyck in England survives. It was compiled by van Dyck's biographer Bellori, based on information from [[Sir Kenelm Digby]].  None of these works appear to remain, except the ''Eros and Psyche'' done for the King (below).<ref name=\"EW\" /> But many other works, rather more religious than mythological, do survive, and though they are very fine, they do not reach the heights of Vel\u00e1zquez's history paintings. Earlier ones remain very much within the style of Rubens, although some of his Sicilian works are individualistic.\n\nVan Dyck's portraits flattered more than Vel\u00e1zquez's. When [[Sophia of Hanover|Sophia, later Electoress of Hanover]], first met Queen Henrietta Maria, in exile in Holland in 1641, she wrote: \"Van Dyck's handsome portraits had given me so fine an idea of the beauty of all English ladies, that I was surprised to find that the Queen, who looked so fine in painting, was a small woman raised up on her chair, with long skinny arms and teeth like defence works projecting from her mouth...\"<ref name=\"EW\" />\n[[File:The Cheeke Sisters by Van Dyck.jpg|thumb|left|''The Cheeke Sisters'', a late double portrait]]\nSome critics have blamed van Dyck for diverting a nascent, tougher English portrait tradition\u2014of painters such as [[William Dobson]], [[Robert Walker (painter)|Robert Walker]] and [[Isaac Fuller]]\u2014into what certainly became elegant blandness in the hands of many of van Dyck's successors, like [[Peter Lely|Lely]] or [[Godfrey Kneller|Kneller]].<ref name=\"EW\" /> The conventional view has always been more favourable: \"When Van Dyck came hither he brought Face-Painting to us; ever since which time ... England has excel'd all the World in that great Branch of the Art\" (Jonathan Richardson: ''An Essay on the Theory of Painting'', 1715, 41). Thomas Gainsborough is reported to have said on his deathbed \"We are all going to heaven, and Van Dyck is of the Company.\"{{sfn|Cust|1899}}\n\nA fairly small number of [[Landscape art|landscape]] pen and wash drawings or [[watercolour]]s made in England played an important part in introducing the Flemish watercolour landscape tradition to England. Some are studies, which reappear in the background of paintings, but many are signed and dated and were probably regarded as finished works to be given as presents. Several of the most detailed are of [[Rye, East Sussex|Rye]], a port for ships to the Continent, suggesting that van Dyck did them casually whilst waiting for wind or tide to improve.<ref>Royalton-Kisch, Martin. ''The Light of Nature, Landscape Drawings and Watercolours by Van Dyck and his Contemporaries'', British Museum Press, 1999, {{ISBN|0-7141-2621-7}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Printmaking==\nProbably during his period in Antwerp after his return from Italy, van Dyck began his ''Iconography'', eventually a very large series of [[old master print|prints]] with half-length portraits of eminent contemporaries. Van Dyck produced drawings, and for eighteen of the portraits he himself [[etching|etched]] with great brilliance the heads and the main outlines of the figure, for an [[engraving|engraver]] to work up: \"Portrait etching had scarcely had an existence before his time, and in his work it suddenly appears at the highest point ever reached in the art\".<ref name=\"Hind\">Arthur M. Hind, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=bxFb8nN_wUQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false A History of Engraving and Etching]'', p. 165, Houghton Mifflin Co. 1923 (in USA), reprinted Dover Publications, 1963 {{ISBN|0-486-20954-7}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Van Dyck Pieter Brueghel the Younger.jpg|thumb|[[Pieter Brueghel the Younger]] from the ''Iconography''; etching by van Dyck]]\nHowever, for most of the series he left the whole [[printmaking]] work to specialists, who mostly engraved everything after his drawings. His own etched plates appear not to have been published commercially until after his death, and early states are very rare.<ref name=\"Decker\">Becker, D. P., in KL Spangeberg (ed), ''Six Centuries of Master Prints'', Cincinnati Art Museum, 1993, no. 72, {{ISBN|0-931537-15-0}}</ref> Most of his plates were printed after only his work had been done. Some exist in further [[state (printmaking)|states]] after engraving had been added, sometimes obscuring his etching. He continued to add to the series until at least his departure for England, and presumably added [[Inigo Jones]] whilst in London.\n\nThe series was a great success, but was his only venture into printmaking; portraiture probably paid better, and he was constantly in demand. At his death there were eighty plates by others, of which fifty-two were of artists, as well as his own eighteen. The plates were bought by a publisher; with the plates reworked periodically as they wore out they continued to be printed for centuries, and the series added to, so that it reached over two hundred portraits by the late 18th century. In 1851, the plates were bought by the ''Calcographie du [[Louvre]]''.<ref name=\"Decker\" />\n\nThe ''Iconography'' was highly influential as a commercial model for reproductive printmaking; now forgotten series of portrait prints were enormously popular until the advent of [[photography]]: \"the importance of this series was enormous, and it provided a repertory of images that were plundered by portrait painters throughout Europe over the next couple of centuries\".{{sfn|Cust|1899}} Van Dyck's brilliant etching style, which depended on open lines and dots, was in marked contrast to that of the other great portraitist in prints of the period, [[Rembrandt]], and had little influence until the 19th century, when it had a great influence on artists such as [[James McNeill Whistler|Whistler]] in the last major phase of portrait etching.<ref name=\"Hind\" /> [[Hyatt Mayor]] wrote:\n\n{{Quote|Etchers have studied Van Dyck ever since, for they can hope to approximate his brilliant directness, whereas nobody can hope to approach the complexity of Rembrandt's portraits.<ref>Mayor, Alpheus Hyatt. ''Prints and People'', Metropolitan Museum of Art. Princeton, 1971, no. 433-35, {{ISBN|0-691-00326-2}}</ref>}}\n\n==Studio==\nVan Dyck's success led him to maintain a large workshop in London, which became \"virtually a production line for portraits\". According to a visitor he usually only made a drawing on paper, which was then enlarged onto canvas by an assistant; he then painted the head himself. The costume in which the client wished to be painted was left at the studio and often with the unfinished canvas sent out to artists specialised in rendering such clothing.{{sfn|Cust|1899}} In his last years these studio collaborations accounted for some decline in the quality of work.<ref>Brown, pp. 84-6.</ref>\n\nIn addition many copies untouched by him, or virtually so, were produced by the workshop, as well as by professional copyists and later painters. The number of paintings ascribed to him had by the 19th century become huge, as with [[Rembrandt]], [[Titian]] and others. However, most of his assistants and copyists could not approach the refinement of his manner, so compared to many masters consensus among [[art historian]]s on attributions to him is usually relatively easy to reach, and museum labelling is now mostly updated ([[English country houses|country house]] attributions may be more dubious in some cases).\n\nThe relatively few names of his assistants that are known are Dutch or Flemish. He probably preferred to use trained Flemings, as no equivalent English training existed in this period.<ref name=\"EW\" /> Van Dyck's enormous influence on English art does not come from a tradition handed down through his pupils; in fact it is not possible to document a connection to his studio for any English painter of any significance.<ref name=\"EW\" /> Dutchman [[Adriaen Hanneman]] (1604\u20131671) returned to his native [[Den Haag|The Hague]] in 1638 to become the leading portraitist there.<ref>Rudi Ekkart and Quentin Buvelot (eds), ''Dutch Portraits, The Age of Rembrandt and Frans Hals'', Mauritshuis/National Gallery/Waanders Publishers, Zwolle, p. 138 QB, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-85709-362-9}}</ref> Flemish painter [[Pieter Thijs]] studied in van Dyck's workshop as one of van Dyck's last pupils.  He became a very successful portrait and history painter in his native Antwerp.<ref name=ox>Hans Vlieghe, \"Thijs, Pieter.\" Grove Art Online. Oxford Art Online. Oxford University Press. Web. 22 August 2019</ref>\n\n[[File:Sir Anthony Van Dyck - Charles I (1600-49) - Google Art Project.jpg|270px|thumb|''[[Charles I in Three Positions]]'' (1635-36), a triple portrait of Charles I, was sent to Rome for [[Bernini]] to model a bust on]]\n\n==Legacy==\nMuch later, the styles worn by his models provided the names of the [[Van Dyke beard]] for the sharply pointed and trimmed goatees popular for men in his day, and the [[Clothing terminology#Costume historian's terms|van Dyke collar]], \"a wide collar across the shoulders edged copiously with lace\".<ref name=\"beard\">{{Cite book |title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Clothing through World History |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-313-33664-5 |editor-last=Condra |editor-first=Jill |edition=1 |volume=2 |publication-place=United States |pages=103 |language=English |asin=B01FJ09WHC |quote=His style coined the names of the van Dyke beard, for the sharply pointed and trimmed goatees popular for men in the first half of the century, and the van Dyke collar, a wide collar across the shoulders edged copiously with lace. |<!--access-date=September 11, 2018-->}}</ref> During the reign of [[George III of England|George III]], a generic \"Cavalier\" fancy-dress costume called a ''Van Dyke'' was popular; Gainsborough's ''[[The Blue Boy]]'' is wearing such a ''Van Dyke'' outfit.  In 1774 [[Derby porcelain]] advertised a figure, after a portrait by [[Johann Zoffany]], of \"[[George III of England|the King]] in a Vandyck dress\".<ref>[[:File:George III, Queen Charlotte and their Six Eldest Children.png|The painting, Royal Collection]]; Honey, W.B., ''Old English Porcelain'', p, 147, 1977 (3rd edn.), Faber and Faber, {{ISBN|0571049028}}</ref>\n\nA confusing number of different pigments used in painting have been called \"Vandyke brown\" (mostly in English-language sources).  Some predate van Dyck, and it is not clear that he used any of them.<ref>\"Vandyke brown\", ''Pigment Compendium'', by Nicholas Eastaugh, Valentine Walsh, Tracey Chaplin, Ruth Siddall, p. 388, 2008, Routledge, {{ISBN|1136373926}}, 9781136373923, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=P7vbXHR2mTYC&pg=PA388 google books]</ref> [[Van Dyke brown (printing)|Van Dyke brown]] is an early photographic printing process using the same colour.\n\nWhen van Dyck was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1632, he [[anglicized]] his name to Vandyke.<ref name=\"Massie\">{{Cite book |title=The Royal Stuarts: A History of the Family That Shaped Britain |last=Massie |first=Allan |publisher=St. Martin's Griffin |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-250-02492-3 |publication-date=5 February 2013 |pages=191 |language=English |type=paperback |quote=Van Dyck was knighted and anglicised his name to Vandyke.}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nThe British [[Royal Collection]], which still contains many of his paintings, has a total of twenty-six paintings.<ref>[http://www.royalcollection.org.uk/collection-search/van%20Dyck?f&#91;0&#93;=sort_creator%3Asir%20anthony%20van%20dyck%20%281599-1641%29%20%28artist%29 Royal Collection] Paintings by Van Dyck</ref> The [[National Gallery, London]] (fourteen works), The [[Museo del Prado|Museo del Prado (Spain)]] (twenty-five Works, such as Self-portrait with Endymion Porter, The Metal Serpent, Christ Crowned with Thorns, The Pretention, Portrait of Mary Ruthven, the painter's Wife), The [[Louvre]] in [[Paris]] (eighteen works), The [[Alte Pinakothek]] in [[Munich]], the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] and the [[Frick Collection]] have examples of his portrait style. [[Wilton House]] still holds the works he did for one of his main patrons, the Earl of Pembroke, including his largest work, a huge family group portrait with ten main figures. Spanish museums own a rich presence of this artist in addition to The Prado's ensemble; The [[Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum]] preserves ''the Portrait of Jacques Le Roy'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museothyssen.org/en/collection/artists/dyck-anthony-van/portrait-jacques-roy|title=Portrait of Jacques Le Roy|website=Museo Nacional Thyssen-Bornemisza|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> property of The Carmen Thyssen-Bornemisza Collection but also on display at the Museum there's  a ''Crucified Christ'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museothyssen.org/en/collection/artists/dyck-anthony-van/christ-cross|title=Christ on the Cross|website=Museo Nacional Thyssen-Bornemisza|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> and The [[Bilbao Fine Arts Museum]] houses a great ''Lamentation before the dead Christ''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museobilbao.com/in/obras-comentadas/van-dyck-anton-57|title=Annotated works {{!}} The Bilbao Fine Arts Museum|website=www.museobilbao.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> In 2008, [[Patrimonio Nacional|Patrimonio Nacional of Spain]] recovered a ''Martyrdom of Saint Sebastian'' and returned it to [[El Escorial|The Escorial Monastery]], two centuries after its removal and, subsequently, The [[Real Academia de Bellas Artes de San Fernando]] has revealed as its own a long-stored painting, added to another , ''The Virgin with the Child with the repentant sinners'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.academiacolecciones.com/pinturas/inventario.php?id=0323|title=Dyck, Antonio van - La Virgen y el Ni\u00f1o con los pecadores arrepentidos|last=Fernando|first=Real Academia de BBAA de San|website=Academia Colecciones|language=es|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> in addition the institution has an original sketch. In addition, in December 2017, a ''Virgin with Child'', which is kept in The [[Museum Cerralbo]] and was previously considered the work of [[Mateo Cerezo]], was revealed as the painter's original after an exhaustive study and restoration project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturaydeporte.gob.es/mcerralbo/coleccion/coleccion0/pintura/anton-van-dyck.html|title=Anton Van Dyck|website=www.culturaydeporte.gob.es|language=es|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Finally, The [[Museu de Belles Arts de Val\u00e8ncia|Museum of Fine Arts of Valencia]] owns an ''Equestrian Portrait of Don Francisco de Moncada'' (currently undergoing restoration, April 2020).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museobellasartesvalencia.gva.es/es/noticias/-/asset_publisher/OCD94WMhKnYX/content/-retrato-ecuestre-de-francisco-de-moncada-de-van-dyck|title='Retrato ecuestre de Francisco de Moncada' de Van Dyck - Noticias - Generalitat Valenciana|website=www.museobellasartesvalencia.gva.es|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Tate Britain]] held the exhibition ''Van Dyck & Britain'' in 2009.<ref>Karen Hearn (ed.), ''[http://www.tate.org.uk/britain/exhibitions/vandyck/ Van Dyck & Britain]'', [[Tate Publishing Ltd|Tate Publishing]], 2009. {{ISBN|978-1-85437-795-1}}.</ref> In 2016 the [[Frick Collection]] in New York had an exhibition \"Van Dyck: The Anatomy of Portraiture\", the first major survey of the artist's work in the United States in over two decades.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.frick.org/exhibitions/van_dyck |title=Past Exhibition: Van Dyck |publisher=The Frick Collection}}</ref>\n\n[[Basilica of St. Joseph Proto-Cathedral|The Basilica of St. Joseph Proto-Cathedral]] in Bardstown Kentucky houses three van Dycks.\n\nThe estate of the [[Charles Spencer, 9th Earl Spencer|Earl Spencer]] at [[Althorp]] houses a small collection of van Dycks including ''War and Peace'' (Portrait of Sir [[George Digby, 2nd Earl of Bristol]], English Royalist politician with [[William Russell, 1st Duke of Bedford]]), which is the most valuable painting in the collection and the favourite of the earl.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4718214/As-a-child-I-loved-the-glamour-of-these-men.html |title=As a child I loved the glamour of these men |date=1999-08-20 |access-date=2019-04-04 |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"220\" heights=\"220\">\nFile:Anthonis van Dyck 004.jpg|''[[Christ Crowned with Thorns (van Dyck)|Christ Crowned with Thorns]]'' (c. 1620) in the [[Prado]]\nFile:Anthonis van Dyck 016.jpg|''Elena Grimaldi'', Genoa, 1623\nFile:Anton van Dyck - Nicolas Lanier - Google Art Project.jpg|''[[Nicholas Lanier]]'', 1628\nFile:Anton van Dyck - The Vision of the Blessed Hermann Joseph - Google Art Project.jpg|''[[The Vision of the Blessed Hermann Joseph]]'' c. 1629\u201330\nFile:Anthonis van Dyck 048.jpg|''[[Rest on the Flight into Egypt (van Dyck)|Rest on the Flight into Egypt]]'', ca. 1630, [[Alte Pinakothek]], [[Munich]]\nFile:Anthonis van Dyck 021.jpg|''Marie-Louise de Tassis'', Antwerp, 1630\nFile:Anthony van Dyck - Charles I (1600-49) with M. de St Antoine - Google Art Project.jpg|''[[Charles I with M. de St Antoine]]'', 1633\nFile:Van dyck tomaso 1634 1635.jpg|''[[Equestrian Portrait of Thomas Francis, Prince of Carignano]]'', 1634\nFile:Anthony Van Dyck - Katherine, Countess of Chesterfield, and Lucy, Countess of Huntingdon - Google Art Project.jpg|''Katherine, Countess of Chesterfield, and Lucy, Countess of Huntingdon'', c. 1636\u201340, oil on canvas, [[Yale Center for British Art]]\nFile:Anthonis van Dyck - Equestrian Portrait of Charles I - National Gallery, London.jpg|''[[Equestrian Portrait of Charles I]]'', c. 1637\u201338\nF